<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Markets Report: US dollar marks time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The truce between central banks and markets held again on foreign exchanges
yesterday, with the dollar trading in a fairly narrow range, writes Philip
Gawith.
The US currency closed firmer in London at DM1.5849, from DM1.5758 on
Monday, and at Y100.210 from Y99.865. It later slipped back in New York
trading, falling below Y100 and DM1.58. It ended the US session at Y99.935
and DM1.5785.
Trading remained fairly quiet, with market participants seemingly unwilling
to take firm positions, faced with the possibility of central bank
intervention and a raft of important events next week.
Although the dollar has been stable, analysts said market sentiment remained
negative with the risks still on the downside.
Elsewhere, sterling received an initial fillip from a bullish set of
Treasury economic forecasts before slipping back in late trading. It closed
at DM2.4513 from DM2.4498 and Dollars 1.5466 from Dollars 1.5547.
The dollar came off its highs for the day after various economic reports
caused a drop in the US Treasury bond market. The conference board reported
that US consumer confidence rose to 92 in June after a revised 88.9 in May,
near to a four-year high. May single family home sales climbed by 4.2 per
cent, after a revised drop of 3.4 per cent in April, while import prices
rose by 1.1 per cent, the biggest monthly gain since October 1990.
These figures fanned fears of inflation, causing weakness in the bond
market, and the dollar repeated the pattern of recent months by falling in
sympathy.
Prior to the economic data, dealers said the dollar had been supported by
rumours of central bank intervention, which failed to materialise.
Mr Tony Norfield, UK treasury economist at ABN-AMRO in London, said it was
only Bank of Japan intervention that was keeping the dollar reasonably
stable against the yen. Many in the market believe that the yen will
strengthen further from current levels.
Swiss Bank Corporation, for example, in its latest currency comment, argues
that 'speculative purchases of yen are about to rise sharply, which makes a
concerted defence of the US dollar most irrational at current levels, and
unlikely'.
Three main factors underpin this view: uncertain Japanese politics, the low
chance of progress on trade talks, and non-Japanese investors reducing their
aggressive short positions in the yen.
The flip side of the more stable dollar has been some evidence of unwinding
of D-Mark positions. Mr Adrian Cunningham, senior currency economist at UBS
in London, said there were 'signs that people were questioning the value of
extending long D-Mark positions at these levels'.
'Risk-reward suggests that you ought to be looking to lock in some short
D-Mark positions for the summer, especially if you expect something might
come out of the G7 meeting.'
The D-Mark continued to give up ground against some of the high-yielding
currencies. It finished at SKr4.802 from SKr4.812 against the Swedish krona,
and at Pta82.42 from Pta82.49 against the Spanish peseta. The Portuguese
escudo closed unchanged at Es102.9 per D-Mark after finance minister Mr
Eduardo Catroga said the currency was correctly valued at its current level.
The Treasury forecast UK growth at 2.75 per cent in 1994, up from its
earlier expectation of 2.5 per cent. It also forecast a 1994/5 public sector
borrowing requirement of Pounds 36bn, down from the Pounds 38bn previously
predicted.
In addition, it revised down its forecast of underlying inflation in the
fourth quarter to 2.5 per cent from the 3.25 per cent prediction made last
November. The impact of these forecasts on sterling was muted by the fact
that they are broadly in line with the consensus.
Some banks have reported recently that orders placed by UK corporates
suggest expectations of a higher pound against the dollar are increasing,
but this is offset by perceptions that the downside risk against the D-Mark
is also rising.
The markets are expecting a further small 3 to 5 basis-point cut in the
German repo rate today after the Bundesbank announced another variable rate
auction.
One factor acting against a larger fall is the level of German call money,
which rose to 5.05/5.15 per cent, from 4.90/5.00 per cent on Monday.
Although the pace of easing has slowed recently, analysts believe that the
strength of the D-Mark allows further room for interest rates to decline.
This view is not fully discounted in the futures market with the December
Euromark contract discounting short term rates of about 5.12 per cent in
December, compared with 4.95 per cent currently. The broking house GNI
argues that fundamentals suggest a bullish view of Euromarks, but says the
bearish tone of bond markets will probably dampen any response.
In the UK money markets, the Bank of England provided Pounds 670m of
assistance after forecasting a Pounds 650m shortage. Overnight money traded
between 4 and 4 7/8 per cent.
</TEXT>
