<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Antimony price surge continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Antimony, a metal with a wide variety of uses, has more than doubled in
price in the past three months, from about Dollars 1,750 to nearly Dollars
4,000 a tonne last night.
Traders said there had been problems with supplies from China, by far the
biggest producer, for some time and the recent price surge was caused by US
dealers buying heavily on behalf of consumers.
When combined with other substances antimony is an extremely useful metal.
It expands when solidifying (a rare characteristic it shares with water) so
is a particularly valuable ingredient of alloys used for castings and type
metal as the expansion forces metal to fill small crevices of casting molds.
Even when added in very small quantities, antimony gives strength and
hardness to other metals, particularly lead, with which it forms alloys used
in plates of car storage batteries, in bullets and coverings for telephone
cables. Among the many applications for antimony compounds, the trioxide and
trichloride are used in flame-proofing fabrics and the trioxide in paints
and plastics both as a pigment and as a fire-retarding agent.
Traders said that consumers could not easily find substitutes for antimony
at short notice and that extra supplies of metal from sources outside China
were not likely to appear until producers were convinced that present high
prices would continue for some time.
Mr Richard Samuels of Lambert International said: 'There seems no reason for
the market to collapse and the price might go a bit higher judging by the
lack of offers and the large number of inquiries we have had'.
</TEXT>
