<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / World Commodities Prices: Coffee consolidates gains as
metals and oil slide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Commodities Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Robusta coffee futures prices rose again in London yesterday after Monday's
40 per cent leap on news of severe frost damage to next year's Brazilian
crop.
Despite fears of a further frost next weekend, the lack of firm details of
the damage kept the rise to 5.5 per cent and the September contract failed
to regain Monday's intra-day high of Dollars 3,150 a tonne. It closed
Dollars 157 higher at Dollars 3,005.
New York remained at boiling point, however. In afternoon trading, the
second position arabica contract was at Monday's high of 170 cents a pound,
up 8.40 cents.
'It's going to take quite a while for people to find out the extent of the
damage,' said Mr Lawrence Eagles, analyst at London brokers GNI. 'One
Brazilian source told me it was nigh on impossible to hire a private plane
because everyone is out flying over the coffee-growing areas.'
Early estimates of the damage suggest anything between 1m and 9m bags of
Brazilian output next year could be lost. But figures vary according to
whether the comparison is with this year's estimated crop of 24m bags, or
the output of up to 30m bags which had been predicted for next year.
Brazil, Colombia and Central America have temporarily suspended export
registrations and Brazil may hold a meeting with other producers in the
region next week to discuss coffee supply.
On the London Metal Exchange meanwhile, base metals prices dropped sharply
before some late bargain-hunting eased the downward pressure late in the
day. Even so, nickel for delivery in three months fell 3.5 per cent on the
day to Dollars 6,045 a tonne; zinc 2.8 per cent to Dollars 945.50; copper 2
per cent to Dollars 2,380.50; and aluminium 1.35 per cent to Dollars
1,457.50.
Mr Ted Arnold, analyst at Merrill Lynch, said the downward moves were
sparked off by profit-taking by US funds and some traders.
'They have built up some big profits in the commodities markets in the past
few weeks,' he pointed out.
'This is not the end of the metals' bull run', he insisted.
The nickel market was affected by a surprise statement from Mr Sergei
Korneyev, sales manager of Norilsk Nickel in Russia, the biggest producer.
He told a Metal Bulletin conference in Moscow that output was holding up
reasonably well and exports could rise by 13 per cent in 1994 compared with
last year's 83,000 tonnes.
Crude oil prices weakened amid expectations that the weekly report from the
American Petroleum Institute would show a marked increase in US stocks. The
price of the benchmark Brent Blend slipped below Dollars 17 a barrel in late
London trading.
Supply bottlenecks in the US at a time of particularly high oil have
underpinned a rise in US crude prices in recent weeks; and that has
influenced the London markets.
But traders said the API report was likely to show that European and west
African producers had reacted to the wide spread between the price of West
Texas Intermediate, the US benchmark, and Brent by sending a large number of
cargoes to the US.
