<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Indian aluminium company plans
output expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KUNAL BOSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BHUBANESWAR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India's National Aluminium Company, which owns the country's largest
integrated aluminium complex, is expecting the federal government to clear
its proposal to expand bauxite (aluminium ore) mining capacity from 2.4m
tonnes to 3.6m tonnes and alumina (aluminium oxide) refining capacity from
800,000 tonnes to 1.35m tonnes at a cost of Rs10.56bn (Dollars 336m).
According to Mr SK Tamotia, the chairman and managing director, however,
Nalco has shelved its plan to build a greenfield, export-oriented alumina
refinery with an annual capacity of 900,000 tonnes.
In the meantime, Hydro Aluminium of Norway, which was to have partnered
Nalco in the alumina venture will be working with Indian Aluminium and Tata
Industries to set up a 1m-tonne export-oriented alumina project at a cost of
Rs22.50bn at Rayagada district of Orissa.
'The reason we backed out of the alumina project is that we are not sure
about its viability,' said Mr Tamotia. 'At the ruling world prices of
alumina, the cost of production will not be covered.'
The company plans to export 400,000 tonnes of alumina in this fiscal year,
compared with 372,000 tonnes in the year to March 31, 1994. 'Nalco is also
planning to expand the aluminium smelting capacity at Angul in Orissa from
218,000 tonnes to 330,000 tonnes,' Mr Tamotia said. 'The expansion is to be
effected by adding one more potline with 240 pots at the Angul smelter.
However, because of our present resource constraint we cannot take up the
project immediately.'
In the meantime, the cost of the smelter capacity expansion has been brought
down from Rs21bn to Rs10bn as Nalco will not be required to create
additional captive power capacity following the assurance of power supply by
the National Thermal Power Corporation.
'India, where the demand for aluminium is growing at an annual rate of about
5 per cent will need extra smelting capacity. Since the cost of setting up a
new smelter will be prohibitive, the existing aluminium producers will have
to expand capacity. Last year, India imported nearly 45,000 tonnes of
aluminium,' said Mr Tamotia.
On paper, India has smelting capacity of 610,000 tonnes. However, this
includes the 73,000-tonne smelter of Indian Aluminium at Belgaum in
Karnataka, which was de-energised in August 1992 because of 'its highly
uneconomic operation'. It is unlikely that the Belgaum smelter will ever
again be recommissioned.
India's eighth five year plan has projected an aluminium smelting capacity
of 772,000 tonnes by 1996-97. Industry officials are unanimous that the
target will not be achieved.
</TEXT>
