<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Capital Markets: MeesPierson sets up fund to
invest in German groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MeesPierson, the Dutch investment bank which is part of the ABN-Amro banking
group, is to launch a DM150m private equity fund which will invest mainly in
'mittelstand' or medium-sized German companies.
The fund is to be run by Mr Onno Hogerzeil and Mr Christopher Peisch, two
fund managers who joined the Dutch institution earlier this year after
running the European investment activities of a buy-out fund for Morgan
Stanley, the US investment bank.
It will invest in small to medium-size companies throughout northern Europe,
although it will concentrate on Germany. The fund will take majority stakes
in companies.
The two managers claim that Germany today offers parallels with the US in
the early 1980s, when the US economy went through significant corporate
restructuring in the aftermath of recession, providing 'many highly
profitable private equity investment opportunities'.
The opportunities are expected to arise as Germany's big industrial
conglomerates sell off non-core businesses. 'The recession has led to a
noticeable change in German companies' attitudes,' observed Mr Hogerzeil,
who said that large companies had abandoned their traditional reluctances to
dispose of subsidiaries.
'Mittelstand' companies are also undercapitalised in relation to their
larger competitors, and MeesPierson hopes that a buy-out fund will offer an
alternative to bank finance as companies seek fresh capital to finance new
investment. They claim there is a growing pool of German managers willing to
undertake buy-outs or buy-ins, still unfamiliar transactions in Germany.
According to Mr Volkert Klaucke, managing partner of MeesPierson in Germany,
the fund is two-thirds placed with institutions, predominantly Dutch pension
funds. The fund will aim for a gross annual yield of 30 per cent. Although
there are dozens of venture capital companies in Germany, there are only a
handful of funds which specialise in buy-ins and buy-outs.
</TEXT>
