<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Bonds: Portugal set to launch DM2bn global FRN
issue today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rumours of a big floating-rate note offering from a European sovereign
borrower which have been in the eurobond market for more than a week proved
true yesterday when details emerged of a DM2bn offering of five-year FRNs
from Portugal.
The issue, which is being arranged by Deutsche Bank, Morgan Stanley and UBS,
is likely to be priced to yield between 9 and 10 basis points over
three-month Libor. It is expected to be launched today.
Syndicate managers said the indicated pricing was fair but they raised some
concern about the size of the offering, in the light of the continued price
volatility in European government bond markets.
However, one manager pointed out that Depfa, the German mortgage bank,
raised DM1bn yesterday without too much difficulty through a domestic
offering of nine-year FRNs at Libor flat.
Some syndicate managers were surprised that Portugal had opted for a global
structure since they did not think there would be huge demand from the US
for FRNs denominated in the German currency.
However, they said the structure would increase the appeal of the FRNs to
central banks around the world.
By contrast, a syndicate manager at one of the joint leads said that the
pre-marketing of the deal had identified strong demand from New York-based
international bond funds who needed floating-rate non-dollar assets.
Portugal's offering will be the first sovereign FRN deal since the beginning
of May, when the Hellenic Republic raised DM1bn through an issue of
seven-year FRNs, with a call and a put option after five years. The
discounted margin on Greece's notes at the launch was 112 basis points over
six-month Libor but yesterday it stood at 122 basis points over Libor,
according to traders.
Among yesterday's deals, Halifax Building Society raised Dollars 150m
through an offering of three-year eurobonds. Lead manager Paribas said the
deal was targeted at retail investors in the Benelux region and in
Switzerland who were attracted by the 6 3/4 per cent coupon.
There were reports that some banks in the syndicate had trouble selling
their allocation, mainly because the Halifax did not have as strong a
following in continental Europe as other UK financial institutions, notably
Abbey National. However, the yield spread widened only slightly when the
bonds were freed to trade.
The proceeds of the deal are believed to have been swapped into
floating-rate sterling.
GECC also tapped the pool of Benelux retail investors with its CDollars 100m
offering of five-year eurobonds.
Lead manager Goldman Sachs said the bonds would coincide with the redemption
of around CDollars 600m worth of bonds in August.
</TEXT>
<XX>
