<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Standard Chartered is called to
account - The bank's abuses may have wider repercussions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Standard Chartered had little option yesterday but to make tough noises
about 'effective management and control' of its investment banking
activities in Hong Kong. The catalogue of regulatory abuse described by the
Securities and Futures Commission (SFC), Hong Kong's corporate watchdog, was
remarkable.
The appointment of Mr John McFarlane, an executive director of the bank, to
oversee the reorganisation of the bank's investment banking business in Hong
Kong, and the clear separation announced between the merchant bank and
securities house, is the beginning of a process, not the end of one.
Last year Standard Chartered Asia was the third largest (ranked by value)
merchant bank in Hong Kong in the lucrative business of initial public
offerings (IPO), and first by number. It has now been banned from this
activity until April next year.
Standard Chartered's profits from Hong Kong broking and merchant banking
were 3 per cent of pre-tax profits of Pounds 401m (USDollars 609.52m) in
1993, with IPOs accounting for about Pounds 1m. But the bank places
strategic importance on broking as Asian capital markets grow stronger and
more sophisticated.
About 20 senior executives and traders from Standard Chartered Securities,
the broker, and Standard Chartered Asia, the merchant bank, have left since
the SFC began its inquiries last October. This includes some of Hong Kong's
leading deal makers who will not be easy to replace.
The infringements from July 1991 until March 1993 include one case in which
the broker lent HKDollars 107m (USDollars 13.84m) to directors of Yanion, a
component manufacturer, to support its HKDollars 750m flotation. In another
case it allowed a company owned by one if its sales directors to
sub-underwrite 10 per cent of an IPO and provided credit lines to enable it
to support the company's share price after the flotation.
In other cases, it permitted its employees to trade against clients through
a practice known as 'rat trading'. This is where trades for customers are
booked through an employee's private accounts with other stock brokers when
the employee judges that he can make a profit.
In terms of the profit and loss account, the upset pales into insignificance
alongside the Bombay securities scandal, which led to a Pounds 269m bad debt
charge in 1992. But it renews long-standing questions about the bank's
ability to control operations in the 50 countries in which it operates.
Mr Malcom Williamson, chief executive, argued yesterday that it was not
comparable with Bombay. 'It would be easy for people to say this is another
India, but that is not really justifiable,' he said. The issue was 'a
reputational one, which we take very seriously,' rather than financial.
Standard Chartered's Hong Kong securities arm was something of a loose
cannon. The operation was formerly a broker called Ching Tung in which the
bank acquired a minority stake after the 1987 crash. It operated as a
largely autonomous subsidiary until full control was taken in the early
1990s.
Risk controls and technology had been upgraded after the integration. But Mr
Williamson said this came too late to prevent the IPO problems. 'The trouble
is that it is easy to get events out of kilter. A lot of this pre-dated our
decision to retain and develop the operation,' he said.
Nonetheless, he acknowledged the potential problems faced by Standard
Chartered in operating in places where regulation is being strengthened.
'Hong Kong was not a highly regulated market until recently, and when you
have an total upgrade of ethics, people can get caught out,' he said.
Indeed, the SFC's rebuke follows on from last September's upbraiding of
Peregrine Investments - Hong Kong's top IPO issuer - for similar abuse of
rules. It was found to have contributed to a restricted free-float in three
IPOs, and was made to pay HKDollars 3.5m to the Hong Kong stock exchange.
The Standard Chartered case, coming less than a year after Peregrine, will
have repercussions beyond the narrow compass of the way an individual
investment house recovers from regulatory censure. It was the judgment of
financial market observers that important parts of the stock exchange's plan
for its future development had been set back, perhaps indefinitely, by
yesterday's revelations.
In particular the exchange's desire to shift some of the regulatory burden
from itself to the merchant banks along the lines of the self-policing
practices apparent in New York - especially in relation to the vetting of
prospectuses - now appears doomed.
As the SFC has been pointing out over the past few months, there are
significant differences between New York and Hong Kong. Some of these
include the general litigious nature of US investors, their ability to mount
class actions against investment houses and the existence of compensation
funds in the US, which many houses maintain in the event of difficulty.
Another important difference is Hong Kong's 1997 transfer to China.
Self-regulation on the scale advocated by the stock exchange would not be
feasible in Hong Kong especially, as one observer delicately put it
yesterday, 'facing the influx of mainland Chinese business practices after
1997'.
The Standard Chartered case has also probably strengthened the SFC's resolve
not to change Hong Kong's prohibition against share price support activities
at initial offerings. These practices are common in the UK and US, and
international merchant banks have been lobbying the SFC in favour of change.
International investment houses have complained to the authorities that
their efforts to launch successfully some of the large mainland Chinese
corporate issues have been hampered by what they regard as 'out of date'
rules under which they have to operate.
It is unlikely that Standard Chartered has helped the case for change.
