<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: SIA and Tata in venture to form
Indian airline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Singapore Airlines (SIA) is planning to launch a domestic airline in India
in a joint venture with Tata Industries, India's leading industrial group.
The two companies yesterday signed a preliminary agreement to form the
airline joint venture, and will carry out a feasibility study and seek the
necessary government approvals.
SIA said this process was expected to take up to six months and, barring
unforeseen circumstances, the new airline should be operational by the end
of next year.
SIA has earmarked India as well as China and Vietnam as significant growth
markets. The airline announced last week a Dollars 10.3bn order for new
Boeing and Airbus airliners to modernise and expand its fleet to meet future
growth.
Liberalisation of the Indian economy and continued strong demand for air
travel in the country was expected to stimulate growth in domestic travel
and tourism in India, both SIA and Tata said.
SIA also said its participation in the new venture was consistent with its
strategy of investing selectively in airlines and associated airport
services in rapidly growing economies of the Asian region.
The joint venture, if approved by the Indian authorities, will also mark the
return of Tata to the airline business. Tata pioneered the industry in India
with Tata Airlines before it was nationalised to become Air India.
SIA also announced yesterday that its Singapore Airport Terminal Services
(Sats) subsidiary was taking a 49 per cent stake in a Dollars 13m joint
venture in-flight kitchen company based at Karachi international airport in
Pakistan.
Sats recently invested in a similar in-flight kitchen venture in Beijing and
the project further reflects the Singapore carrier's expansion drive in
fast-growing Asian air travel markets.
</TEXT>
