<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Corning shares jump as sales
soar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Corning jumped by more than 6 per cent as the US manufacturing
group beat market expectations with strong sales growth in its second
quarter.
Corning lifted post-tax profits to Dollars 111.4m, or 54 cents a share,
compared with Dollars 89.8m, or 47 cents a share, in the same period in
1993.
Revenues in the three months to June 19 were Dollars 1.1bn, up 22 per cent
from a year before - though around half of the growth stemmed from the
acquisition last year of Damon, a medical testing company.
The rest was due to the stronger US economy, which had a positive impact on
all the company's main businesses, Mr James Houghton, chairman, said.
Corning also benefited from stronger earnings in associated companies,
primarily Dow Corning. This, and the elimination of losses with the disposal
last year of its interest in Vitro Corning, led to reported income of
Dollars 34m from associates, up from Dollars 27m a year before.
For the first half, Corning's net income rose to Dollars 169m, or 82 cents a
share, from Dollars 139m, or 73 cents, a year before. Its shares closed at
Dollars 33 1/8, up Dollars 1 7/8 on the day.
