<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Ontario Hydro shake-up urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ontario Hydro, the biggest power utility in North America, urgently needs to
reassess its structure as a government-owned monopoly to cope with growing
competitive and financial pressures, according to a report commissioned by
the utility.
Although the report makes no firm recommendations, its authors, led by
Hydro's chief financial officer, clearly signal their preference for at
least a partial privatisation.
A group of financial advisers, including three US and Canadian investment
banks, concluded that 'the market appetite for an initial issue of Ontario
Hydro equity would be in the order of CDollars 5bn (USDollars 7bn)'. The
offering would include an international component.
However, a final decision on Hydro's future rests with the provincial
government. The left-of-centre New Democratic Party has resisted
privatisation but allowed the utility to proceed with a restructuring which
has already resulted in 7,000 job losses.
The shake-up has been spearheaded by Mr Maurice Strong, who took over as
chairman in late 1992 after a career in diplomacy, which included organising
the Rio summit on the environment.
The report concludes that 'the need for change is urgent and stakeholders
will have to make significant choices soon if the competitiveness of our
electric power industry is to be sustained and if Ontario Hydro's assets are
to retain their value'.
It notes that the Canadian power industry cannot afford to be out of step
with the increasingly competitive climate in the US, where deep discounts
are being offered to industrial customers. Furthermore, a capital infusion
is required to redress the lop-sided balance sheet, which carries CDollars
34bn of debt supported by less than CDollars 4bn of equity.
Unexpectedly slack demand for electricity in recent years has left Hydro
with substantial surplus capacity.
</TEXT>
