<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: US-German deal to create
third-biggest reinsurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Re, the biggest US reinsurance company, has agreed to take indirect
control of Germany's Cologne Re, a move that would create the world's
third-biggest reinsurance grouping.
Cologne Re had premium income of DM4.5bn (Dollars 2.7bn) in 1992, the most
recent figures available, while General Re had premiums of Dollars 2.5bn in
1993. Together, the two would still be smaller than two other European-based
groups, Munich Re and Swiss Re.
General Re described its planned alignment with the German company as an
'association'. However, the deal, which has yet to be finalised, would give
the US company ultimate control.
The plan is for Colonia, the German insurance group, to transfer its 75 per
cent interest in Cologne Re to a new company, which would, in turn, be
majority-owned by General Re. In return, the US reinsurer would pay an
unspecified amount of cash and securities, part of which would be used to
boost Cologne Re's capital.
The proposed deal represents General Re's first big move out of its home
market, where it generates 90 per cent of its premium income. It would make
it one of the biggest companies in international reinsurance.
Rumours about a possible joint venture between Cologne Re and a foreign
company have circulated in Germany since early June. Mr Klaas Kleyboldt,
chief executive at Colonia, confirmed last week that talks were under way.
However, he stressed then that Colonia had no intention of selling its stake
in its reinsurance subsidiary.
The new alliance is consistent with the strategic restructuring of the
Colonia group, which was set in motion by Mr Kleyboldt after the German
group became a majority-owned subsidiary of the French Union des Assurances
de Paris (UAP). France's biggest insurance group took control of Colonia
last October with the aim of challenging Allianz, the Munich-based company,
as Europe's largest insurance group.
</TEXT>
