<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Opel head blames industry woes
for DM503m deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Herman, chief executive of Adam Opel, blamed 'the worst year in the
automobile industry in a decade' for a loss of DM503m (Dollars 320.4m) at
General Motors' German subsidiary last year.
The loss, which followed a net profit of DM259m in 1992, was likely to be
followed by a 'dramatic improvement' during the current year, the chief
executive said.
Mr Herman declined to expand on this, saying there were a number of
uncertainties ahead. 'We don't know how quickly Germany can free itself from
recession,' he said.
Opel had returned to profitability in the first six months of the year, said
Mr Gail Gunderson, finance director. However, he warned that it was unlikely
to make a profit in the year as a whole.
Market share of new cars registered in Germany in the first five months of
1994 was down by 1 per cent to 15.6 per cent. Mr Herman blamed this on poor
availability of the new Omega model early in the year, and predicted that
market share would be back to 17 per cent by the year-end. The Omega alone
was expected to win a 3 per cent market share.
The depth of the downturn last year was reflected in a 21 per cent fall in
the number of Opel cars registered in Germany, from 671,000 to 530,000, a
decline which translated into a drop in market share from 17.1 to 16.6 per
cent. Turnover for the German operations was down from DM29.1bn to DM21bn
last year, a 21 per cent fall.
The results were hit by a DM360m loss on currency translation, and a charge
of DM370m to cover early retirement and other rationalisation measures.
There were further, unspecified costs associated with the change to
production of the new Omega and Corsa models.
The losses at Opel in Germany helped hold down profits at the Opel/Vauxhall
group in Europe, to just under DM1bn, Mr Herman said yesterday. General
Motors is the overall market leader in Europe with a 12.5 per cent share.
Mr Herman said that between January and May this year, Opel's market share
had risen in 11 European countries.
He declined to give details on the state of litigation in the case of Mr
Jose Ignacio Lopez de Arriortua, the former General Motors director who
joined rival Volkswagen last year. Mr Herman confirmed that the US Justice
Ministry had lodged a formal request for judicial help with its Bonn
counterpart. He also cast doubt on a report compiled by the KPMG accountancy
firm exonerating Mr Lopez from being in possession of confidential material
belonging to General Motors, as GM alleges.
</TEXT>
