<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Siemens sells pacemaker unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Siemens, the Munich-based electronics and electricals group, is selling its
US-based cardiac pacemaker manufacturing business for 'slightly over'
Dollars 500m. The buyer is St Jude Medical, a manufacturer of artificial
heart valves and blood pumps based in St Paul, Minnesota.
The pacemaker business generated Dollars 350m in turnover for Siemens last
year. Siemens said the sale was driven by strategic considerations, in view
of changes in the market for products implanted during heart surgery,
including artificial blood vessels, valves, heart muscle pumps and
artificial hearts.
Physicians and hospitals had previously bought individual products from
different companies, but there was now a trend towards 'single-sourcing',
Siemens said.
This trend was encouraging the development of companies providing the full
spectrum of products.
Siemens supplies a range of products to cardiologists, but its activities in
the field of cardiac systems for implantation are limited to pacemakers.
It said yesterday it had decided to sell the business - the second biggest
manufacturer of pacemakers in the world - rather than seek to expand across
the full range of implantation products.
Siemens is the world's largest manufacturer of medical systems, with total
sales of DM7.9bn (Dollars 5.03bn) in this area last year. It said the
pacemaker business was profitable, and that sales had risen consistently in
recent years.
A total of 1,300 employees will move to St Jude as a result of the sale.
The sale will take effect in the fourth quarter of Siemens' current
financial year, which ends on September 30.
</TEXT>
