FT  29 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Enlarged Debenham Tewson improves 44%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pre-tax profits of Debenham Tewson &amp; Chinnocks, one of the few quoted estate
agents and chartered surveyors specialising in commercial property, rose by
44 per cent, from Pounds 2.86m to Pounds 4.12m during the 12 months to April
30.
The company also announced that Mr Anthony Turnbull intends to step down as
chief executive at the beginning of next year. Mr Mark Struckett, currently
managing director of the company's London operations, becomes group managing
director.
Turnover rose 40 per cent to Pounds 57.6m (Pounds 41m). Earnings per share
rose to 6.17p (5.13p) and the final dividend is increased to 2p for a total
of 3.5p (3p).
The company, which last year merged with Bernard Thorpe, has expanded its
regional network as well as increasing international operations. Mr Richard
Lay, chairman, said that the results showed that the policies were starting
to bear fruit.
On the general state of the commercial property market, he said: 'We have
seen a reversal in the trends of previous years and a significant recovery
in the capital values of commercial investment property as yields have
fallen to reflect the reduction in short term interest rates.
'However, we have not yet seen any return to growth in rental values across
the country and until this does occur we shall not enjoy a sustainable
recovery in our markets.'
