FT  29 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Clinton shares fall on profit warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Clinton Cards fell sharply yesterday after the specialist retailer
warned that profits were unlikely to exceed last year's Pounds 3m.
The group, which claims 7 per cent of the UK greetings card market, also
said that its seasonal loss for the first half to end-July would be
'significantly higher than last year's Pounds 1m.'
An interim deficit is normal, as the chain is dependent on Christmas
trading.
The shares lost 31p to close at 105p.
Sales in the core business of cards and wrapping paper had been flat, the
group said. However, sales of gift products and ancillary lines have been
significantly below last year. Mr Barry Hartog, finance director, put this
down to a lack of fresh products based on popular characters such as
Garfield and Mr Blobby.
Like for like sales have fallen by 4 per cent, although overall sales have
risen 3 per cent on the back of an increase in the number of outlets. The
group is now trading from 279 shops, compared with 273 last year, and
further branches are planned.
In March the group reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 3.02m on sales of
Pounds 75.9m, ex-VAT, up from Pounds 2.3m on sales of Pounds 68.2m. At the
time Mr Don Lewin, chairman, said that consumer confidence seemed to be
'rather fragile, fuelled perhaps by worries about personal tax increases'.
