<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Midlands Electricity at top endof City
forecasts with Pounds 195m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Midlands Electricity yesterday reported pre-tax profits at the top end of
City forecasts for the 12 months ended March 31.
On turnover slightly lower at Pounds 1.42bn (Pounds 1.54bn) the pre-tax
figure rose from Pounds 167.1m to Pounds 195.4m.
The performance was helped by a 2.7 per cent increase in units distributed,
double the average national increase, and a reduction in the staff of its
regulated businesses by 424 people, or 7.5 per cent of the total.
The regulated distribution business turned in profits of Pounds 142m (Pounds
144.3m) after Pounds 20.8m of restructuring costs. The supply business
reported profits of Pounds 33.4m (Pounds 18.8m) after a Pounds 4.2m charge.
Mr Bryan Townsend, chairman, said he expected the review of the recs'
distribution to be tough and he could not forecast what dividends the
company could pay out in future years.
The company swung from net debt of Pounds 6m in March 1993 to net cash of
Pounds 167.3m at the latest year end. Unlike most other recs it owes no
money to the government.
Earnings per share rose to 65.2p (55.8p) and a final dividend of 15.55p
lifts the total by 16 per cent to 23.2p.
The company will seek shareholder approval at its annual meeting to buy back
up to 10 per cent of its own shares.
COMMENT
Shareholders might have been surprised at a Pounds 2m fall in distribution
profits to Pounds 142m but there is no need for alarm. Midlands is one of
the few companies which has chosen not to collect its full entitlement from
consumers under the price controls. That means there is a Pounds 10.8m
under-recovery in distribution, rising to perhaps double that by the end of
this year. If things get nasty with the regulator, Midlands could claw that
back. Similarly, the supply under-recovery is likely to be about Pounds 15m
by the year-end. The Pounds 195m headline profit is also depressed by the
decision to make a Pounds 25m provision for restructuring costs. In
addition, the company has Pounds 12.5m salted away to cope with potential
problems over pensions which may never be needed. The market is perhaps a
little nervous about Midlands' expansion abroad and about the effect of the
regulatory review on the sector. But the shares, up 23p to 575p yesterday,
are trading on a prospective yield of 5.8 per cent assuming a dividend of
26.4p this year, and look underpriced compared to other regional companies.
</TEXT>
