<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / The Lex Column: Arjo Wiggins
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Papermakers are smiling again. Prices and volumes for many paper grades are
rising nicely with a wave of stock replenishment being succeeded by a
pick-up in underlying demand. Eucalyptus pulp prices have risen by more than
50 per cent since the fourth quarter of 1993. The Swedish manufacturer,
MoDo, yesterday pushed prices higher on several grades. Given the huge
operational gearing in paper companies, such rises rapidly translate into
surging profits.
But just as life eases for paper manufacturers, their share prices are
starting to soften. Arjo Wiggins Appleton, for example, has underperformed
the FT-SE All-Share by 7 per cent over the past three months having
outperformed by 46 per cent over the previous year. The market had already
anticipated much of the good news. Besides, concerns are now focusing on
what type of paper cycle it will be this time.
Arjo Wiggins Appleton has worked to depress the cyclicality of its earnings
in the hope they will be rated more highly at the next peak. The group's
exposure to higher value added papers, its merchanting arm and geographical
spread all promise a higher quality of earnings. But as commodity producers
accumulate cash, they can be relied on to over-invest in new capacity. They
would perhaps do better to buy each other and thus consolidate an
unhealthily fragmented industry. Takeover talk would then be another reason
for pushing paper shares higher.
</TEXT>
