<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / The Lex Column: Standard's deviation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Standard Chartered seems to have enormous difficulty breaking with its past.
The bank protests that its latest troubles in Hong Kong go back to a time
before its management and risk control were strengthened, but there is
inevitably a sense that Standard is simply accident-prone. If the market
shrugged off the latest announcement, this may have been because it has not
involved a financial loss while much of the detail was already known. Coming
hard on the heels of the Bombay debacle, though, it raises questions about
inherent risks in developing country banking and, in that context, how
deeply involved a bank like Standard Chartered should be in local securities
markets.
Arguably Standard's business is one of high rewards accompanied by high
risks. Few other UK banks could produce a net return on ordinary
shareholders' funds to match the 21 per cent managed by Standard last year.
Yet few also run the risk of operating in the domestic markets of a broad
range of developing countries. The market will always have to take account
of that when rating the shares. Hence consensus forecasts put Standard on a
multiple of around eight times 1994 earnings, which is at a discount to the
sector.
Improved risk control could enhance the rating of Standard's shares, but the
market will take time to be convinced that the new management is effective
on that score. Standard could also staying away from securities and
concentrate on safer businesses like trade finance at which it excels. That,
however, would be a strategic sacrifice. Economic growth will increasingly
lead Asian companies to raise funds in the securities market rather than
through banks. If Standard withdrew from that business, it would be piling
up risks of a different sort for the future.
</TEXT>
