<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Observer: Iriplaceable
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Running Iri, Italy's giant state holding company, has invariably proved a
thankless job. Maybe that's why Silvio Berlusconi's door has no anxious
queue of contenders outside it.
No one is hurrying to replace departing chairman Romano Prodi. Berlusconi
and his boys have yet to fix on a suitable candidate. Time is running out -
Prodi is leaving on Thursday, after Iri's annual meeting.
One front-runner still appears to be Ennio Presutti, the 63-year-old head of
Assolombardo, the Lombard business federation and Italy's most powerful
regional business lobby.
His credentials are impeccable. Though Roman-born, he is an honorary
Milanese through his work, and thus in sympathy with the predominant
'northern' strain in the government.
Presutti made his career with IBM in a host of senior executive posts in
Italy and Europe. He also has numerous board directorships in the private
sector. On paper, precisely the kind of managerial experience needed to wind
up a debt-ridden and outmoded institution such as Iri.
There's a catch. With a cv like his, Presutti appears rather too radical for
the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance ministers. After all, Iri was a
Mussolini invention and a central pillar of his corporatist state . . .
</TEXT>
