<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Postman Pat and his E-mail cat: Post offices do have a
commercial future - if they adapt to new technology
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In 1873 the US postmaster-general predicted that Alexander Graham Bell's
telephone would supplant written mail. In fact, the western world's postal
services are busier than ever. But can they continue to withstand the march
of competition and technology?
The question is of special interest to investors across Europe, who are
likely to be offered shares in a succession of postal privatisations over
the next decade. The Dutch mail operator was privatised last month. The UK's
Post Office is clamouring to follow - a government consultation paper on its
future may be published later this week.
Eager to convince a sceptical public, Britain's Post Office argues that its
future is safe only if it is privatised. It cites competition to deliver
business mail from, among others, the Dutch operator, and new forms of
communications such as fax machines. 'No letter is safe from the
technological postman,' claims Mr Bill Cockburn, chief executive. 'At the
moment the technology is ahead of the market. But when the market catches
up, we will be highly vulnerable unless we can invest.'
The case for privatisation is alluring. The Post Office says it has only
about 14 per cent of the UK 'communications' market, including mail,
telecommunications, and electronic media. Across the world, the telecoms
operators are rapidly being exposed to competition: until recently yoked
together with postal operators across Europe, they are now forging
multi-billion international alliances geared to the corporate market and
talking about still larger investments in fibre-optic 'superhighways'. With
nine-tenths of all UK mail paid for by the corporate or public sectors, the
Post Office's argument goes, the future could be grim unless it is allowed
to behave in a similarly aggressive and entrepreneurial fashion.
In reality the Post Office is almost certainly overstating its case. It
assumes, first, that commercial freedom requires privatisation and, second,
that a failure to develop new lines of business will inevitably undermine
its existing service.
Neither is necessarily the case. In practice, argues Mr Adrian King, a
postal expert at Omega Partners, a London-based consultancy, three broad
challenges face post offices across Europe - liberalisation, competition and
new technology. But in each area the threat is less straightforward than it
might initially seem. Liberalisation of services in the European Union is
proceeding far more slowly in postal services than in telecoms. The EU has
yet to produce firm plans but draft proposals circulating in Brussels
suggest that the post offices will be able to protect their letter
monopolies on the grounds that they are needed to ensure a universal
service.
Competition, particularly in liberalised markets such as parcels, will
certainly intensify. But the total cake will grow; the arrival of the
technological postman will probably create more, not less, footslogging for
his human counterpart. Transactions made by E-mail and fax beget orders and
statements; home shopping begets home parcel deliveries. The Post Office's
main asset, a home-to-home delivery service, is not about to become
obsolete. While every other utility has shed jobs in the past 20 years, the
Post Office's workforce has risen from 170,000 to 190,000 in response to
demand for its services.
As further competition is allowed, some advertising mail may be delivered to
homes by rivals to the Post Office - including companies already active in
the parcels and express delivery sectors. But apart from premium
business-to-home services, rivals will be interested mostly in low-priority,
low-value advertising business which does not require elaborate sorting
facilities or daily deliveries.
Meanwhile, direct mail is greatly expanding the market for business-to-home
communication. For example, Heinz, the food company, has switched a large
part of its marketing budget to direct mail. New technology offers several
ways of bypassing the post box - notably fax, E-mail, electronic data
exchange and 'hybrid mail' (letters that are collected, sorted and printed
electronically and then delivered by hand). However it is simplistic to
suppose post offices are under immediate threat or ill-equiped to respond.
Only parts of the mail market appear susceptible to early competition.
According to Mr King, the standard European pattern is for 10 per cent of a
postal service's traffic to be household-to-household, 60 per cent
business-to-household, and 30 per cent business-to-business.
The use of physical mail is unlikely to diminish markedly in the first
category. In the third, the technological postman is more threatening as
E-mail, fax and other electronic links are hard to match with physical
delivery services.
But in the second category - business to home - technology offers post
offices an opportunity to expand business by pioneering the use of hybrid
mail. The challenge is to expand total traffic and for post offices to gain
a far larger slice of its value by becoming one-stop providers of electronic
printing and home delivery services. That could extend to providing data
bases, billing software and payments systems using post offices' own giro
cash transfer facilities and counters.
'The task of post offices is to move up the value chain,' says Mr King. 'It
is not so much competition from other deliverers, but gaining a larger slice
of the value of postal and electronic communications which challenges them.'
The case of Sweden Post, arguably Europe's most advanced operator in new
technologies, is instructive. Although wholly state-owned, it has a free
rein to take commercial decisions on alliances and investment strategy, and
no longer has a monopoly over letter deliveries. It is one of Europe's few
profitable post offices (the UK's is another), and has a subsidiary, called
PostNet, dedicated to developing electronic communications.
'The prospect of competition on the mail side forced us to take electronic
media seriously,' says Mr Bengt Norin, an executive director of Sweden Post
hired from a US software company to build up Sweden Post's electronic side.
The competition in the letters business has come mainly from City Mail, an
independent company, which offers a delivery service, about twice-weekly, in
Stockholm and other cities including Goteborg and Malmo. In spite of
Sweden's large rural hinterland, Sweden Post believes it can continue to
offer a universal service by retaining a large share of the high-value
delivery business in cities. The government will review the position in
three years; if Sweden Post argues at that stage that it cannot continue
nationwide letter deliveries, levies on rival operators could be imposed to
subsidise the service.
By then Sweden Post expects electronic communications to be a substantial
part of its business: last year, of the 2.5bn first and second class letters
handled by Sweden Post, 200m were hybrid mail. It also transmitted several
million electronic messages via E-mail or data exchange systems.
Sweden Post's principal hybrid service is 'ePost', which enables companies
to despatch, electronically, statements and other printed mail to six
centres across the country, where the material is printed and put into the
ordinary mail. A 'PC ePost' service, just launched, allows smaller customers
to send hybrid mail from desktop computers.
In the E-mail business the main competitor is Telia, the state telecoms
operator. Mr Norin denies Telia is the 'natural' player in the electronic
market. 'We don't own the roads because we drive on them: anyway, they are
going to have their hands full with new cable and voice services over the
next decade.'
Telia, of course, does not see it that way. The electronic highways of
Europe are set to become battlefields between telecoms operators - and the
more entrepreneurial post offices.
