<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Perverse pensions proposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr GUY THOMAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, As noted in your reports, 'Pensions: the white paper' (June 24), the
government's proposals to abolish guaranteed minimum pensions will bear most
heavily on early leavers from pension schemes. As a group they can be
expected to suffer a significant reduction in the rate of revaluation
applied to their deferred pensions. For at least two reasons, it is perverse
that this group should be chosen to be the main losers in the current round
of reforms.
First, the 'early leaver problem' - the poor level of revaluation applied to
early leavers' deferred pensions - was the focus of a previous pensions
controversy a decade prior to the Maxwell affair. Thus, a problem partially
addressed in the mid-1980s is to be exacerbated a decade later.
Second, it is widely recognised that employment patterns are becoming more
fragmented, with an increasing preponderance of short-term employment over
'jobs for life'. In the course of a career, most employees can now expect to
be early leavers from several pension schemes, each providing a modest
deferred pension which will be progressively eroded in real terms relative
to earnings inflation. Thus, changes in the labour market, coupled with the
white paper's proposals, will mean that the early leaver problem will become
both more widespread and more severe.
It is strange that a package of reforms with the stated intention of
restoring confidence in occupational pension schemes should accentuate their
prime disadvantage relative to personal pensions, and thus serve to
accelerate the ascendancy of the latter. But perhaps this is the ulterior
purpose which the government has in mind?
Guy Thomas,
lecturer in actuarial science,
University of Kent,
Canterbury CT2 7NF
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
