<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Complexities of gas market
competition not to be underestimated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr NORMAN BLACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Ted Trafford and others (Letters, June 24) suggested that
introduction of competition into the domestic gas market will result in
winners only. However, solutions to many of the complex problems raised in
the Department of Trade and Industry/Ofgas consultation paper have yet to be
found.
British Gas is certainly not against competition - provided the playing
field is level. Competitors already hold 46 per cent of the non-domestic
market. However, introducing competition to 18m domestic homes is a mammoth
task and the complexity should not be underestimated. The Monopolies and
Mergers Commission report warned against the rapid introduction of
competition and the DTI/Ofgas consultation document confirmed that there
would be price variations for different customers.
Legislation will inevitably be complicated. Customers need to be guaranteed
safety and security of supply. Arrangements also need to be put in place to
protect the more vulnerable members of society, including the elderly,
disabled and those with difficulties in paying their bills. Further
investment in infrastructure is vital to maintain the pipeline system and to
meet customers' future demands. We have connected more than 2m homes to the
system in the last seven years and our total investment has exceeded Pounds
7bn.
British Gas has delivered good value and good service at home, and this
expertise applied overseas has enabled us to become the leading
international gas company, directly benefiting the UK economy.
The challenges of introducing competition into the domestic sector are
extremely complex. We will be working to make it a success.
Norman Blacker,
managing director,
gas business, British Gas,
Rivermill House,
152 Grosvenor Road,
London SW1V 3JL.
</TEXT>
