<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today we are promised a unique insight into the lives of two men. The more
tempting is BBC2's programme about artist KB Kitaj whose largest exhibition
opened this month at the Tate. He has never before agreed to be filmed, so
Kitaj - In The Picture is unusual (11.15). Programmes about the other man,
Prince Charles, are not unusual. The idea that his difficulty is merely one
of 'image', that all he needs is a more efficient PR effort to match his
wife's, a second generation Dimbleby to act as 'gold microphone in waiting'
(Malcolm Muggeridge's memorable phrase for Richard Dimbleby) and that all
will then be well, is surely wrong. On the contrary, it is less publicity
that will preserve the mystery and magic of monarchy. In today's 2 1/2 -hour
promo for the Windsors plc on ITV, Charles: The Private Man, The Public Role
(8.00), the prince might have avoided this being seen as yet another 'charm
offensive' had he had the courage to come clean about his relationships with
Diana Spencer and Camilla Parker Bowles. But industry talk suggests that,
although raised, the issue is fudged.
</TEXT>
