<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Business and the Environment: A fruitful alternative - St
Lucia needs tourism but hopes to escape the ravages seen in other resorts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In his bright new hillside office above the St Lucian capital of Castries,
Richard Peterkin regrets that his Caribbean island did so little to prepare
for life without bananas.
'We knew what was coming,' says Peterkin, a partner in the local offices of
management consultants Price Waterhouse, referring to St Lucia's shrinking
banana market in Europe.
'The unfortunate thing is that in these islands there are not a lot of
alternatives to bananas,' he adds.
A lush, sunny island, blessed with sandy beaches, does have one alternative,
of course: tourism. Whatever their misgivings, most people on the island
accept that tourism will have to support the livelihoods of a growing number
of its 150,000 people.
For decades, St Lucia's bananas, along with those of other former British
and French colonies, have had privileged access to much of the European
Union, which has applied quotas and tariffs on bananas from Latin America.
However, the drive for freer world trade has led to St Lucia's privileges
being gradually reduced.
As its agricultural sector shrinks, the island, a relative newcomer to
tourism, is striving desperately to avoid some of the environmental and
social ravages that have followed the development of the industry elsewhere.
The growth of tourism on the island, which gained independence from Britain
in 1979, has been accompanied by debates echoed in holiday destinations
around the world.
Should the island build large resort hotels, with their own restaurants and
leisure facilities? Or should it encourage smaller hotels, so that tourists
buy their food in local shops and restaurants? How can it ensure that the
benefits of tourism spread to the wider population rather than being
restricted to a few, usually foreign, hotel owners? Above all, how can St
Lucia persuade the 375,000 visitors to the island each year that it has a
history and culture worth learning about?
'There is more to this country than just lying on a beach and drinking rum
punch all day,' says Stephen McNamara, one of the island's leading lawyers
and chairman of the St Lucia Tourist Board.
Despite its small population, St Lucia has produced two Nobel Prize winners:
Sir Arthur Lewis, for economics, and the poet Derek Walcott, for literature.
There is some resentment in St Lucia over the attitude of tourists from
wealthier countries who often regard the island as little more than an
alluring escape from harsher climates and a more frenetic pace of life.
In 1948, long before tourism became the international industry it is today,
Walcott worried about his island:
'Found only
In tourist booklets, behind ardent
binoculars;
Found in the blue reflection of eyes
That have known cities and think
us here happy.
St Lucia has made several attempts to present itself to the tourist market
as a country with much more to offer than sun and sea.
It recently hosted an international jazz festival, its third.
McNamara says the tourist board is looking at ways of developing St Lucia as
a destination for fishing tournaments.
The most vigorous debate on the island, however, concerns not what tourists
should do when they get there but where they should stay during their
holiday.
Cletus Springer, permanent secretary at the tourism ministry, says that
two-thirds of the island's 3,100 hotel rooms are in inclusive resorts -
those in which the visitors pay for their meals in advance.
Restaurateurs on the island have complained that the growth of all-inclusive
hotels has deprived them of business. Other critics say the hotels are
denying St Lucians access to the publicly owned beaches and that they buy
most of their supplies abroad.
The reputation of the hotels for being unsympathetic to the island's
population has been exacerbated by allegations of maltreatment from a local
barrister and a musician.
The complaints from the restaurateurs have led to the establishment of a
government task force, chaired by McNamara, which reported earlier this
year. It found that all-inclusive hotels have the advantage of achieving
higher occupancy levels and room rates than their conventional counterparts.
The task force says, however, that local farmers should view all-inclusive
hotels as a market for food and vegetables. This would enable farmers to
move away from their dependence on bananas.
The island has launched a scheme called Adopt-a-Farmer. Under the scheme,
hotels offer a guaranteed price to a local farmer for specified quantities
of fruit and vegetables, provided they are of sufficiently good quality.
The scheme is still in its infancy, with six farmers so far participating.
But there is some scepticism about its prospects. One local businessman
says: 'They've been trying to do this sort of thing for donkey's years. You
can buy these things much more cheaply in Miami. That's a fact of life.'
The government is attempting to boost business in other areas. Current
legislation provides import and other tax exemptions for hotels, allowing
them to bring in many of their supplies free of duty.
A new law is being prepared to extend these privileges to restaurants,
owners of water sport facilities and other tourism-related businesses.
But, above all, the government says it is determined to keep the development
of tourism under control. Springer says St Lucia does not want to have more
than 5,000 hotel rooms available on the island, a figure it expects to reach
by the end of the decade.
But with unemployment on the island running at 20 per cent, many doubt
whether the government will keep hotel developers out after the 5,000 rooms
have been built.
Keith Martel, general manager of Windjammer Landing, a local hotel and
resort, says: 'At the end of the day, money talks. If there is a proposal
for another all-inclusive resort there will be an absolute hue and cry on
the island. But I can't see the government turning it down.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>LCZ  St Lucia, Caribbean.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7999 Amusement and Recreation, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
