<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Business and the Environment: Labels to cut back logging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Indonesia, one of the world's biggest forestry producers, is to introduce an
eco-labelling system for wood products. The move comes in response to
criticism from environmentalists about the scale of illegal logging in the
country.
The scheme, to begin on an experimental basis this year and to become fully
operational in 1997, will label all wood products with information about
where the wood originated and how it was processed.
Although the Indonesian government will be involved in the scheme,
Djamaludin Surjohadikusomo, the forestry minister, says he hopes it
eventually will be independent of government. It will be headed by Emil
Salim, the former environment minister, and non-governmental organisations
will be invited to participate.
'The forestry industry needs a sustainable supply,' says Djamaludin, a
former forester. 'Without it, the industry will commit suicide.'
The government may provide some initial funding, but Djamaludin says he
would like to see the scheme financed by the industry or international
agencies.
The initiative has been welcomed by leading environmental groups. 'The
eco-labelling debate is a way of bringing a lot out into the open,' says
Suraya Afiff of Walhi, the local branch of Friends of the Earth.
Walhi has estimated that illegal logging amounts to as much as 30-40 per
cent of the 30 cu m of timber which are officially logged each year.
Djamaludin puts it much lower - at 4-6m cu m.
Mohammad Hasan, who controls ITCI, one of the country's largest timber
companies, and also heads Apkindo, the powerful plywood trade group, says
fairness requires that countries producing non-tropical timber should also
have eco-labelling schemes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IDZ  Indonesia, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
