<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / People: John Page moves from the grass roots to advise
Barclays
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
John Page, the next head of agricultural services at Barclays Bank, believes
British farmers can best survive the rigours of the CAP reform by knowing
precisely what market they are producing for.
Page, 53, who takes over in September, comes from the agrochemicals side of
the industry. He has been director of the British Agrochemicals Association
since 1989, which has meant regular contact with the agriculture ministry
and the departments of environment and trade and industry.
The 24-strong agricultural services department of Barclays focuses on the
financial and policy outlook for agriculture, advising branches on
agricultural lending and farmers on business management.
'It's going to be a very exciting time for British agriculture, with new
crops and new opportunities,' says Page. 'I think farming should move away
from the concentration on commodities towards growing specialist crops on
contract, with the purpose for which they are grown very much in mind from
planting onwards. That will reduce the dependence on (financial) support
that some sectors have now.'
Page does not work the soil himself. But his grandfather was an Essex farmer
and Page worked on a farm for two years while studying for a national
diploma from the Royal Agricultural College, Cirencester.
From there he joined a seed, fertiliser and agrochemicals distributor as a
sales representative before moving to ICI Agrochemicals as technical
development and marketing manager. He then became general manager of Atlas
Interlates, a company which develops and markets agro-chemicals.
At Barclays he replaces Paul Ingram, who is retiring.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Barclays.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
