<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Spending by credit card up sharply in all sectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further signs of the strength of high-street spending emerged yesterday
after the Credit Card Research Group reported that expenditure on credit and
debit cards rose sharply in all sectors last month.
The group, which conducts research on behalf of the industry, said that
total spending on cards in the three months to May was Pounds 14.05bn, 17
per cent higher than in the same period a year ago.
Spending on credit and debit cards in May itself was Pounds 5.07bn. This was
slightly better than in April, and markedly up on the level in March.
In contrast to other pick-ups earlier this year, the rise in credit-card
spending was now spread across all high-street sectors, the group said.
Food and drink accounted for the largest part of the total credit-card and
debit-card spending, with Pounds 1.037bn spent in this category last month.
Measured on a quarterly basis, food and drink expenditure was Pounds 2.93bn,
22 per cent up on a year ago.
Credit-card and debit-card spending in department stores and on mail order
was 14 per cent higher, while clothing was 16 per cent up compared with the
same quarter last year.
The group welcomed the figures as evidence that the tax rises had not yet
dented consumer spending. However, it added that the growth may also have
reflected consumers' growing use of credit cards in place of cash or
cheques.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6141 Personal Credit Institutions.
</IN>
<XX>
