<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / It's official: Budget increases will not tax recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It's now official. In the Treasury's view, the tax increases of last year's
two Budgets will not stall Britain's economic recovery.
The Treasury's summer economic forecast, published yesterday, revised up the
prediction of economic growth this year to 2 3/4 per cent from 2 1/2 per
cent at the November Budget. It also projects growth of 2 3/4 per cent next
year in the government's first official forecast for next year.
At the same time, underlying inflation, as measured by the retail prices
index excluding mortgage interest payments, is projected to be 2 1/2 per
cent in the final quarter of this year, substantially lower than the 3 1/4
per cent forecast in the Budget. At the end of next year, the Treasury
expects underlying inflation of 2 3/4 per cent, still within the
government's 1 per cent to 4 per cent target range but above the lower half
of the band in which the government has pledged to have inflation by the end
of this parliament.
The prices charged by manufacturers at the factory gate are also likely to
be moving up by the end of next year. Although the Treasury expects producer
output price inflation to fall to 1 1/2 per cent by the end of this year
from 2 per cent in May and 3 per cent in autumn last year, it expects a rise
to a 'temporary peak' of 2 1/2 per cent by the end of next year, reflecting
more expensive raw materials, higher unit wage costs and pressure by
companies to increase margins.
The Treasury has been able to build its more upbeat assessment of Britain's
prospects on improvements in the world economic outlook. US growth in
particular picked up more sharply than expected in the second half of last
year and appears to have kept up momentum in the first half of this year.
While a question mark still hangs over Japan, there are 'more convincing
signs of recovery' on the European continent. Growth in the Group of Seven
leading industrial nations as a whole is now forecast to be 2 1/2 per cent
this year -  1/2 percentage point above the Budget forecast - rising to 2
3/4 per cent next year.
Recent monthly indicators 'suggest that the economy continues to have plenty
of upward momentum' with retail sales 'on a strong upward trend' and
business surveys pointing to 'continued healthy expansion of manufacturing
output in the months ahead'.
Although the forecast says growth of consumer spending may slow a little in
the short term as a result of tax increases, this is not expected to be
reflected in gross domestic product.
The forecast notes that car registrations have weakened in recent months
while recovery in the housing market has stalled. But it does not seem too
concerned by these developments.
Instead, the Treasury expects the personal savings sector ratio, which fell
last year to 11 1/2 per cent from 12 1/4 per cent in 1992, will fall further
this year to less than 10 per cent. This, and a quickening of disposable
income growth to 2 1/2 per cent next year from 1 per cent in 1994, should
enable consumers' expenditure to increase by 3 per cent both in this year
and next.
The forecast expresses measured optimism about the corporate sector and
investment. Profitability, which started to recover in 1992, is expected to
strengthen further this year. Although business investment has yet to show
signs of improving after last year's 1 1/2 per cent fall, the Treasury sees
increases of 3 1/2 per cent this year and 7 per cent next year.
Investment in private dwellings and land, which rose just  1/2 per cent last
year, is forecast to increase 4 per cent this year and 4 1/2 per cent next
year.
The UK's current account balance of payments, which showed a Pounds 11bn
deficit last year, is forecast to continue in the red but not to
deteriorate. The Pounds 9 1/2 bn shortfall forecast for this year is
unchanged from the projection in the November Budget. A further current
account deficit of Pounds 9 1/2 bn has been forecast for next year.
The Treasury expects the visible trade deficit, which was Pounds 13 1/2 bn
last year, to be unchanged this year and to narrow to Pounds 12bn next year.
Summer Economic Forecast, HM Treasury. HMSO. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
