<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Treasury makes big cut in gilts funding needs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday announced a substantial Pounds 5bn downward
revision in the volume of gilt-edged securities that it will need to sell in
this financial year even though it is cutting only slightly its forecast for
the public sector borrowing requirement.
In its summer economic forecast, the Treasury envisages a PSBR of Pounds
36.1bn, equivalent to 5 1/4 per cent of gross domestic product, for the year
to the end of March 1995 compared with Pounds 38bn forecast in the November
1993 Budget.
But sales of gilts will have to total only about Pounds 32bn in 1994-95 to
meet the objective of fully funding the deficit compared with an estimate in
March this year of gilt sales of Pounds 37bn. Of the Pounds 32bn, the Bank
of England has already sold gilts worth Pounds 4.55bn since the beginning of
April.
To arrive at the Pounds 32bn, the Treasury said it has carried over a
cumulative overfund of the 1993-94 deficit that it estimates at Pounds 2 1/4
bn. Against this, some Pounds 8 1/2 bn of gilts are expected to mature in
1994-95. With foreign currency reserves assumed to stay unchanged on
balance, the overall funding requirement for the current financial year is
forecast at about Pounds 42bn compared with Pounds 47bn three months ago.
National Savings are expected to contribute about Pounds 3 1/2 bn towards
funding the deficit while a further Pounds 6.8bn of gilt-edged securities
sold to banks and building societies in 1992-93 will be counted towards
funding before the end of this financial year.
The government expects a further improvement in the UK's public finances in
1995-96. The PSBR for the coming financial year is now forecast at Pounds
27.9bn compared with the Pounds 30bn forecast in the November Budget. If the
1995-96 target is met, the PSBR will have fallen to 4 per cent of GDP from 7
1/4 per cent in 1993-94, when the deficit totalled Pounds 46bn.
The Pounds 2bn improvement now expected in the 1994-95 PSBR mainly reflects
a Pounds 1.9bn increase in revenues expected this year. The principal change
is an expected Pounds 1 1/4 bn increase in corporation tax receipts compared
with the Budget forecast, which largely reflects better than expected
profits in 1993.
The Treasury said yesterday that its forecasts for income tax and value
added tax are also higher than in the Budget, but these are offset partly by
downward revisions to the forecast receipts from petroleum revenue tax,
excise duties, business rates and capital gains tax.
Although unemployment has fallen more sharply than expected in last
November's Budget, the government expects only a modest Pounds  1/4 bn
decline in cyclical social security payments in the current financial year
compared with earlier forecasts. Improved privatisation proceeds are
expected to play an important role in reducing the PSBR for 1995-96. The
government now expects that sales of electricity company debt and equity
will boost privatisation income to Pounds 2 1/2 bn in the coming financial
year from Pounds 1bn predicted in the November Budget.
The government's PSBR projections could be overturned by any changes to
existing tax and spending plans in the Budget on November 29 this year.
At present, however, the Treasury envisages that tax as a share of GDP will
increase sharply to 37 per cent by the end of 1995-96 from about 34 per cent
in 1993-94.
