<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Six London radio licences attract 41 bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Radio Authority yesterday received 41 applications for six London radio
licences including 12 applications to provide an adult contemporary music
service - aimed at an audience aged between 25 and 50.
The groups fighting for the right to fill what they see as the big remaining
gap in the London commercial radio market - playing music such as Elton
John, Fleetwood Mac and Simply Red - include: Chrysalis, the music and
entertainment group; televiTrans World Communications, the radio group;
Metro, the Newcastle commercial radio station that is trying to break into
the London market; Emap, the magazine and radio group; and Energy London, a
consortium led by the French commercial radio group NRJ.
Mr Richard Eyre, managing director of Capital Radio, which yesterday
reapplied for its two London licences, warned that launching an adult
contemporary service would tend to cannibalise Capital's audience and
advertising revenues without offering the maximum possible diversity.
The Radio Authority is required to seek applicants who offer the maximum
possible choice for the 6.2m to 7.3m adults expected to be covered by the
new licences.
In addition to the two licences that are expected to be retained by Capital,
two new FM and two new AM licences are on offer.
Mr Richard Branson, who runs Virgin 1215, the national AM commercial
station, and who previously failed to win a better quality FM national
licence, is trying again in London. Virgin Radio has applied for an FM
licence to broadcast 'existing Virgin 1215 rock-orientated music output with
speech content specific to London'.
Apart from adult contemporary and other popular music there are applications
for classic and album rock, alternative, and soft music services, as well as
for two arts services.
Art FM is promising a mixture of entertainment and arts coverage with
non-pop music while Festival Radio is offering independent music, comedy,
arts, interviews and listings.
A number of formats that failed to win a licence last time are trying again.
These include London's Business radio, London Christian Radio and Viva -
speech and music in a magazine format aimed at women listeners.
There are also two competing sports services, a range of ethnic and
international broadcasting aimed at Arabic-speaking and Pakistani listeners
plus Radio France Internationale and a service for parents of pre-school
children.
The intense interest in the new licences is a further sign of the growing
attractiveness of commercial radio.
Last year revenue in the sector grew by 26 per cent to Pounds 178.5m. This
was because of the higher profile generated by the new national stations and
the better selling of radio advertising, which added up to a record 3.4 per
cent of all advertising. Some analysts now believe a 5 per cent share for
radio is possible.
The Radio Authority will decide which of the 41 applicants will get licences
by this autumn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
