<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Tighter rules on university status
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, yesterday tightened the criteria
that higher education institutions must meet to achieve university status.
He told the Higher Education Quality Council, the self-regulating body, that
institutions would need to have taught degree courses to at least three
year-groups - taking five years in total for three-year courses - before
they could award degrees in their own right. They would then need a track
record of not less than three years of 'successfully maintaining degree
standards'.
Only about five or six higher education colleges are interested in becoming
universities.
