<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Changes to legal training proposed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Fundamental changes in education and training for solicitors and barristers
in England and Wales have been put forward by the Lord Chancellor's Advisory
Committee on Legal Education and Conduct.
The committee yesterday published a consultation paper on the initial stages
of legal education covering law degrees and conversion courses for non-law
graduates.
It proposes that a prescribed common element to law degrees should be
retained but the emphasis should move away from subjects to be studied, such
as contract, tort and crime, to a small number of broad aims, such as
understanding the fundamental principles and concepts of English and EC law
and an understanding of law's social, economic, political, historic, ethical
and cultural context.
</TEXT>
