<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Copier leasing industry warned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Photocopier leasing companies criticised in March by the Office of Fair
Trading for unscrupulous selling practices have been given three months to
clean up the industry or risk losing their consumer credit licences, Robert
Rice writes.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, yesterday said the
industry had until the end of September to meet higher standards of
transparency in leasing contracts.
He told the Institute of Trading Standards Administration conference in
Brighton that he believed in freedom of contract within wide limits. But
onerous contract terms such as long-term leases for machines with short
lives, or lease and service-inclusive cost-per-copy contracts, with an
obligation to pay for a minimum volume of usage, should be drawn to
customers' attention.
Sir Bryan said: 'Engaging in misrepresentation or deceitful selling
practices, or failing to observe high standards of transparency about all
the main terms and conditions of a contract, are likely to be inconsistent
with fitness to hold a consumer credit licence.'
He has said that he will carry out a further review of the industry at the
beginning of next year.
</TEXT>
