<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / McDonald's fights 'poisoning' claim
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The McDonald's fast food chain yesterday asked the High Court in London to
halt a campaign by environmentalists accusing it of poisoning customers,
exploiting Third World countries and employing cheap labour.
A leaflet distributed four years ago contained a 'wholesale attack on almost
every aspect of McDonald's business', said Mr Richard Rampton QC.
It was 'completely false in every material respect', he told Mr Justice Bell
at the start of a libel action expected to run for up to four months.
Yet London-based environmental campaigners Mr Dave Morris and Ms Helen Steel
had published, as recently as the day before, material repeating the
allegations.
McDonald's, said Mr Rampton, was seeking to protect its reputation for
'uniform excellence' in the quality of its products, the well-being of its
customers, the welfare of employees and respect for communities and the
environment.
Mr Rampton was explaining why the world's biggest food service organisation,
with 14,000 restaurants in 70 countries, was pressing ahead with its action.
Mr Morris, 39, and Ms Steel, 28, who say their allegations are justified,
are unwaged and conducting their own defence because they cannot afford
lawyers. Legal aid is not available in libel actions. They are members of
the London Greenpeace group, which has no connection with Greenpeace
International.
McDonald's has no prospect of recovering more than nominal damages or its
legal costs, which could run to more than Pounds 1m. Mr Rampton made clear
that the main purpose of the action was to secure an injunction banning them
from repeating their allegations.
Mr Rampton said the allegations in the 'malicious' leaflet - entitled
'What's Wrong with McDonald's? Everything They Don't Want You to Know' - had
begun to appear with alarming frequency in the 'respectable media', both
nationally and locally.
The case is being heard without a jury because the courts have ruled that
the issues require careful and prolonged examination of complex scientific
evidence culminating in a reasoned judgment.
Mr Rampton said the dispute was not about freedom of speech because the
freedom laws did not extend to the dissemination of falsehoods about other
people.
'There may well be people who don't like McDonald's food, either because it
is made from meat or because they don't like the taste, and they may wish to
give expression to their views, sometimes in strong terms,' he said.
'McDonald's may not like it, but would not try to stop honest criticism.
What they will always seek to prevent is the dissemination of false factual
information about the company, its business and its products.'
The hearing continues today when the defendants will outline their case.
</TEXT>
