<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / DoT land purchases attacked: National Audit Office says
Pounds 1.1bn spending for roads was mostly unnecessary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Transport has spent more than Pounds 1.1bn since 1986 on
acquiring land and property to build roads, most of which are unlikely to be
needed, says a report to be published today by the National Audit Office.
The public expenditure watchdog says delays in finalising the route of trunk
roads and motorways force the department to buy far more property than is
eventually needed.
It also criticises the department for wasteful management of its growing
estate. Property records are incomplete, rent arrears are more than double
the target level, vacancy levels are too high and sales of surplus property
take too long, the NAO says.
The government's road-building plans mean the transport department has been
acquiring and managing increasing amounts of property. Property-owners
blighted by plans for new roads and road widening can ask the department to
buy their property. But the NAO found that about 60 per cent of properties
bought under these provisions were not required when the final route for
road schemes was decided. In one scheme for widening junctions on the M20
motorway, 78 per cent of the property bought was not needed.
The main reason for the unnecessary purchases is delay in finalising
preferred routes, says the NAO. In the cases examined for the report it had
taken an average of 10 years to decide a preferred route after announcing a
scheme. Two schemes took 20 years or more.
Some Pounds 220m was spent buying property in 1992-93, and just Pounds 10m
released by selling unwanted parts of the estate. Annual spending on
acquiring land had increased by 200 per cent in three years.
The cost to the department of managing its estate was Pounds 4.3m in
1992-93, bringing in rental income of Pounds 7.5m. The management of much of
the property is contracted out to seven housing associations, a residential
property agent and seven commercial and agricultural agents.
Rent arrears of Pounds 2m had accumulated by March 1993, more than Pounds
500,000 of which was judged by the agents to be irrecoverable.
The level of arrears, 21 per cent of collectable rents, was more than double
the department's target. More could be done to collect the arrears, the NAO
says. An additional Pounds 300,000 a year could be brought in by charging
market rents, the NAO estimates. And further action is needed to reduce
vacancy levels, running at a quarter of the estate.
The NAO also found that almost a third of the land no longer needed for
roads had been held for more than the three-year target set by the
department for disposal - in many cases for avoidable reasons.
Department of Transport: Acquisition, Management and Disposal of Land and
Property Purchased for Road Construction. HMSO. Pounds 8.15.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
