<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Reactor-grade plutonium was used in bomb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Reactor grade' plutonium - produced in commercial reactors - can be used to
build nuclear bombs, according to information released by the US energy
department.
The department revealed in a 200-page statement declassified on Monday that
plutonium from a UK reactor was used in 1962 for detonating a nuclear bomb
at the US underground test site in the Nevada desert.
Greenpeace, the environmental group, has said that British Nuclear Fuels'
Thorp plant at Sellafield in Cumbria could lead to the spread of nuclear
weapons capability. The plant, which started operating earlier this year,
extracts plutonium from used reactor fuel, and plans to send it to overseas
nuclear power companies, particularly in Japan and Germany.
The UK government has argued that plutonium from civil reactors does not
pose a security threat because constructing a bomb from the fuel is
extremely difficult. However, the Department of Trade and Industry said
yesterday: 'This test proves that it (using plutonium from reactors to make
bombs) is possible. But our understanding is that the difficulties involved
in practice were such that no one would really dream of trying it.'
The plutonium used in the US test was derived from military work carried out
by the UK Atomic Energy Authority at the Calder Hall reactor at Sellafield,
the DTI said.
BNF said yesterday: 'We have always said you need considerable skill to make
bombs from reactor-grade plutonium, not that it is theoretically
impossible.'
Ms Janet Bloomfield, who chairs the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, said:
'This shows that all those who gave categoric assurances that Thorp's
plutonium cannot be used for nuclear weapons, and accused CND of
scaremongering, were lying.' And the Washington-based lobby group, Nuclear
Control Institute, called on Britain to 'halt . . . needless production of
weapon-usable plutonium'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
