<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Employers told to win backing on pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employers who do not intend to allow employees to appoint representatives to
pension-scheme boards of trustees will have to prove that the employees have
agreed to forgo their rights, a government discussion paper proposed
yesterday.
The Department of Social Security has released a discussion document
following last week's white paper on pension reform. It spells out how
proposals allowing members to appoint up to a third of their scheme trustees
will work in practice.
The document says that employers will have to consult both employees and
pensioners on opting out of the member-trustee requirement. Employers will
then have to hold a referendum to show that members have genuinely agreed to
forgo their rights.
Many large schemes already have member trustees although some are appointed
by management. Some trustees may also be appointed by unions.
The government said it did not wish its new law to upset existing
arrangements which had proved satisfactory to both scheme members and
employers.
Schemes which opt out of the member-trustee requirement should be allowed to
do so for no more than six years at a time before being asked to review the
arrangement.
Under the proposals existing trustees should be responsible for determining
appropriate procedures for the nomination and selection of member-nominated
trustees, although employees should have the right to challenge those
procedures.
Also, no employer should be allowed to remove a member-appointed trustee,
even if that employee is sacked or leaves voluntarily. Member-trustees may
only be removed by a unanimous vote of the remaining trustees or by the new
pensions regulator, the proposals suggest.
</TEXT>
