<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Institute chief tells accountants to be more open
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountancy firms should provide greater details of their own financial
strength, the new president of the UK's largest chartered accountancy body
said yesterday.
Speaking shortly after his inauguration as president of the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, Mr Roger Lawson told the
Financial Times that the firms should be more open.
'It is entirely appropriate that there should be greater transparency for
buyers of services so they can be satisfied of the financial strength or
otherwise of the people with whom they are doing business,' he said.
'People really should be in a position to have greater confidence in the
direction (of the firms) and not that they are just trading on brand names,'
he said, in a reference to the powerful image of the largest accountancy
firms.
His plea comes at a time when KPMG Peat Marwick, the UK's second largest
firm, is considering moves towards incorporation.
Mr Lawson argued that there may ultimately be a move towards an independent
review of the finances or at least the insurance assets claimed by firms in
the light of a growing number of lawsuits against them.
'It might be better if a mechanism could be found for a third party in whom
everyone had confidence to examine the figures,' he said, adding that there
would need to be safeguards to ensure that competitor information was not
passed between the firms.
Mr Lawson's remarks partly reflect his experience as an accountant in
business, unlike most of his predecessors, who were in public practice. He
works for 3i, the venture capital company.
The accountancy firms - as partnerships rather than companies - are
currently under no obligation to reveal details of their financial
performance or strength.
They are highly secretive organisations. While often urging greater
disclosure from their corporate clients they have always resisted providing
such information themselves.
Senior partners of the firms have rejected such arguments, claiming that
people would not understand the figures for profits allocated to each
partner, which include pension costs and dividends as well as salary.
Mr Andrew Colquhoun, secretary and chief executive of the institute, said
that greater disclosure was the responsibility of the firms and that the
institute would only intervene if such a change was proved to be in 'the
public interest'.
</TEXT>
