<PROFILE>_AN-EF2DYABUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Package targets four economic sectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese government's third deregulation package of the past year is
more concrete in content than its predecessors, but woollier in its timing.
No action can be taken on the 279 regulations it schedules for review or
abolition until the package is approved by the cabinet. That depends on the
speed with which a new government can be conjured from the present political
wrangling between Japan's three main political blocs. Mr Eijiro Hata,
minister of international trade and industry, predicted, however, the next
cabinet would adopt the package without changes.
So the plan is a statement of good intentions. It lacks details of an
extension of the present one-year income tax cut, put on hold since last
weekend's collapse of the government. 'That is now up to discussions between
parties,' said a government official. As such, the package is likely to earn
the highest praise from the US, which eagerly awaits evidence of progress in
stimulating domestic demand and reducing Japan's trade surplus.
But once a new government is in place, officials believe 193 regulations
will be on the scrap-heap by the end of this year and 36 next year, with the
timing of the rest uncertain.
Yesterday's deregulation plan covers four main sectors: housing and land,
telecommunications, access for imports, and the financial markets.
On housing, the most important changes are the acceptance of foreign tests
for imported building materials and a relaxation of the restrictive planning
zones which are a factor in Japan's cramped urban living conditions. Thanks
to zoning laws, an estimated 5 per cent of privately owned land in Tokyo is
officially supposed to be for agricultural use.
The government has stopped short of easing rules on entry into the
telecommunications service market, a disappointment to potential newcomers
who had encouraged speculation that the door would be thrown open. However,
the plan does promise to clarify approval criteria for new
telecommunications services.
It intends to ease government price controls on some kinds of
telecommunications services and make it easier for private sector telephone
services to connect with the public system, a liberalisation step urged by
foreign companies.
On imports, the plan proposes that foreign safety tests should be more
widely accepted on cars, car parts, food, drugs and medical devices coming
into Japan. Currently they have to obtain tests from often expensive and
overworked Japanese laboratories to qualify for import licences. Japanese
technical standards should also be adjusted to international levels in these
areas, says the plan. It also calls for more liberal application of the
large-scale retail law, which controls the opening of new shops.
The package is part of a five-year campaign to purge more than 10,000
official rules and permits which restrain some 40 per cent of the economy.
Despite efforts by previous governments to reduce the tangle of red tape,
the number of regulations grew for seven years running until 1993.
This reflects opposition from some ministries reluctant to see their powers
eroded, and protected business sectors, like small distribution companies
and corner shops, which are loath to face competition.
Government officials now believe the pile has started to shrink, as the
political drive for deregulation has started to gain momentum. It is a
feature of a gradual liberalisation of the Japanese economy, helped by
international competition and the growth of free market thought among the
country's biggest businesses.
The first two packages of the current deregulation drive, in September and
February, condemned 881 rules to abolition. Of that total, 595 - or two
thirds - have actually been scrapped. Another 111, requiring legislation,
are stuck in a lengthening queue of parliamentary bills, held up by the
series of political crises over the past year. More deregulation packages
are planned.
The Keidanren, which has switched over the past few years to an enthusiastic
advocate of deregulation, from its previous conservative defence of vested
interests, appeared impressed by the latest step.
Mr Geoffrey Barker, chief economist at Baring Securities in Tokyo, added:
'It certainly covers the right areas, but the pace of change will depend on
the political will of the next government.' As Mr Hosokawa's deregulation
packages show, the hard bit is putting good intentions into practice.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
