<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Presidents of divided Korea to hold talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRADLEY MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The presidents of North and South Korea are to meet next month for the first
time since the Korean peninsula was divided after liberation from Japanese
colonial rule at the end of the second world war.
Agreement to hold the summit in Pyongyang from July 25 to 27 was reached
yesterday during a tense eight-hour meeting of officials at Panmunjom in the
demilitarised zone between the two countries. Presidents Kim Young-sam and
Kim Il-sung monitored the negotiations on television from Seoul and
Pyongyang.
The possibility of a summit was opened up earlier this month during the
visit to Seoul and Pyongyang of former US president Jimmy Carter.
The breakthroughs which followed the Carter visit - US and North Korean
officials are also to hold talks in Geneva from July 8 - have put into
abeyance US-led efforts to impose United Nations sanctions on North Korea in
retaliation for its refusal to permit full international inspections of its
nuclear facilities.
Mr Carter received a package of proposals from Mr Kim Il-sung for resolving
the dispute, including his acceptance of a proposal from the South Korean
president for a summit.
After the announcement of the summit between north and south, a Seoul
government spokesman said: 'This is a historic agreement. It will go a long
way towards resolving pending issues . . . and easing tensions on the
peninsula. The precious fruit we reaped today will serve as a foundation for
. . . ending the history of national division and moving towards peaceful
reunification.'
Mr Lee Hong-koo, the south's chief delegate, said: 'Both presidents have
moved to make a political decision to ease tension on the Korean peninsula
at a time when the peninsula remains an exception. The rest of the world is
trying to seek co-operation rather than confrontation.'
For the North, Radio Pyongyang said the two sides would seek an atmosphere
'favourable to reconciliation, unity, trust and understanding'.
</TEXT>
