<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / China spectre stalks HK vote: Simon Holberton previews
debate on governor's franchise bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The vote today in Hong Kong's Legislative Council (LegCo) on Governor Chris
Patten's democracy legislation looks likely to be close and both the
governor and his opponents will be lobbying undecided members right up to
the end.
The success or failure of Mr Patten's attempt to broaden the franchise for
LegCo's 1995 elections will turn on the votes of one or two of the 60
legislators. 'Whatever the outcome it is not going to be good,' said one of
the governor's opponents.
The principal threat to Mr Patten's legislation comes from amendments
proposed by the Liberal party, a 15-member conservative grouping of mainly
appointed politicians, which wants to limit the franchise to Hong Kong's
traditional plutocracy. They have attracted independent members of LegCo who
point to strong support among the colony's business community.
Where Mr Patten wants to enfranchise Hong Kong's 2.3m working population,
the Liberals want to restrict the vote to 122,000 businessmen. And where Mr
Patten wants an electoral college itself composed of 346 popularly-elected
officials, the Liberals favour those elected by a restricted vote.
The Liberals and their supporters believe that a bill amended along these
lines has a better chance of surviving under Chinese rule than does Mr
Patten's. This is in spite of China's threat to annul the result of the 1995
elections when it resumes sovereignty of Hong Kong in 1997. 'There is no
other viable choice,' says Mr Howard Young, the Liberal who will move the
party's amendments today.
For the governor's part, Mr Patten's advisers tell him that support for his
legislation has improved from 26 votes to nearly a majority. 'Our assessment
is that we have enough votes to win,' said one official.
Mr Patten - who was described yesterday by an official as looking
'baggy-eyed and grim-faced' - has been criticised by some pro-democracy
politicians for not trying hard enough to persuade wavering legislators. His
aides deny this, pointing to a check list of meetings he has had with
undecided LegCo members over the past weeks.
'We are lobbying hard for this bill,' said one aide. 'We are not agnostic
about this process.'
The outcome of the vote could be decided by a handful of Beijing's
supporters in LegCo. In a week when China appears prepared to settle a
long-running dispute with Britain about defence lands in Hong Kong and the
financing of the colony's new airport, Beijing may just want to show Mr
Patten who is boss.
China's importance to today's deliberations arises because there is no
system of pairing in LegCo. When votes are close, those who abstain have an
important impact on the outcome. Beijing, which has three faithful
supporters, usually abstains on constitutional matters.
The current arithmetic is that if China's supporters do abstain, Mr Patten
will win the vote. If they decided to support the Liberals' amendments then
the vote could be tied or Mr Patten may lose.
Articles in the pro-Beijing Wen Wei Po and Ta Kung Pao newspapers yesterday
stressed that no matter what LegCo decided today, fresh elections would be
held in 1997.
Yet, according to Mr Tsang Yok-sing, chairman of the pro-Beijing Democratic
Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong, voting for the Liberals'
amendments was 'the only possible option - if the Liberals are defeated then
most probably Mr Patten's bill will go through intact.'
China's indirect participation in the vote would make it much more difficult
for it to sustain opposition to what LegCo decides. Hitherto China has
treated LegCo as an instrument of an illegitimate colonial regime - a mere
advisory body, at best.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>HKZ  Hong Kong, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
