<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / US consumer confidence at 4-year peak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A rebound in consumer confidence this month and a rise in sales of new homes
in May were seen yesterday as confirming the underlying strength of the US
economic recovery.
On Wall Street, the unexpected buoyancy of the indicators prompted falls in
bond prices in early trading - on the grounds that signs of economic
strength would increase the chance of an early increase in short-term
interest rates.
The Conference Board said its closely followed index of consumer confidence
rose to 92 this month from a revised 88.9 last month. The level of
confidence in the second quarter was the highest for four years.
Mr Fabian Linden, for the board, said confidence was at a level that
historically 'has been associated with a reassuringly lively economy'.
Consumers, however, were still concerned about the availability of jobs.
Confidence, however, varies significantly by region. It is buoyant in
central, southern and mountain states but still quite subdued on the east
and west coasts.
Sales of new single-family homes rose 4 per cent from April to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 738,000, 16 per cent above the level in the same
month last year.
The figures follow recent reports - on retail sales and industrial
production - that appeared to signal a deceleration in the underlying pace
of economic growth from an unsustainable annual rate of about 5 per cent in
the second half of last year. If growth does slow to an annual rate of 3 per
cent or less in the second half, the domestic pressure on the Federal
Reserve to raise interest rates will be reduced.
Fed governors and regional presidents meet in Washington on July 5 and 6 to
set monetary policy. Some analysts expect the Fed to signal another increase
in short-term rates to support the weak dollar. Others believe the Fed will
continue to focus on the domestic outlook for inflation and growth and wait
until employment figures for June are released on July 8 before making a
decision on rates.
</TEXT>
