<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Feisty Rivlin would press hard for fiscal discipline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
In nominating Ms Alice Rivlin as budget director on Monday, President Bill
Clinton has chosen a feisty, straight-talking economist who will press hard
for responsible fiscal policies.
The nomination was yesterday welcomed by Washington insiders as just reward
for a long record of competence in budgetary matters.
Ms Rivlin gained the respect of legislators in both political parties during
her long tenure as founding director of the non-partisan Congressional
Budget Office from 1975 to 1983.
She also exerted considerable influence on policy through books and articles
written over several decades while a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, a centrist Washington think-tank.
Some observers, however, were surprised that Mr Clinton should have chosen
somebody with whom he lacks a personal rapport as budget director, one of
the most powerful jobs in an administration. The Office of Management and
Budget director is responsible for the annual federal budget and exercises
broad oversight over the main spending programmes.
'She will speak her mind even when it's not what the White House wants to
hear,' said Mr Bruce MacLaury, president of the Brookings Institution.
Ms Rivlin has other advantages. She is keener on deficit reduction than
anybody else in the administration and her appointment is a way of
signalling to financial markets the continuing importance placed on budget
retrenchment. Bond prices rose following the announcements on Monday,
although this probably reflected hope that Mr Leon Panetta's appointment as
chief of staff would introduce some much needed discipline to the White
House.
Mr Clinton was also able to reaffirm his commitment to promoting women and
minorities and thus to making his administration 'look like America.' If, as
expected, Ms Rivlin sails through Senate confirmation hearings, she will
become the first female budget director in US history. The Clinton
administration will be the first to have two women in top economic policy
positions, with Laura D'Andrea Tyson already chairing the Council of
Economic Advisers.
Ms Rivlin's most important task initially will be to try to prevent
healthcare reforms increasing the budget deficit. But her ability to
influence the more general course of fiscal policy will be limited. The main
fiscal decisions for Mr Clinton's first term were taken in the 1993 budget:
further deficit-cutting measures of any significance are improbable despite
pleas for further action from bodies such as the International Monetary
Fund.
Ms Rivlin brings less political expertise to the job than Mr Panetta, a
long-serving congressman from California. She may make good this deficiency
by selecting a Capitol Hill insider as deputy.
</TEXT>
