<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Wage rise threatens Brazil prices move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's government plans to increase minimum wages by nearly 8 per cent
from September, in a move that could undermine efforts to beat inflation
through the Real currency, due to be launched on Friday.
In an effort to cut inflation from around 50 per cent a month, Brazil
intends to link the Real at parity with the US dollar and limit the amount
of the new currency to be issued.
The finance ministry and central bank had also been seeking a delay in
increasing the minimum wage, to give these anti-inflationary measures time
to take hold.
However, President Itamar Franco has now agreed to an increase in the
minimum monthly wage from Dollars 65 (Pounds 42) to Dollars 70, ahead of a
'full review' later this year.
The government has suggested that calls for an increase in the minimum wage
to Dollars 100 have been defeated. But the president's agreement to the
increase will add to pressure from Brazil's military, who are pushing hard
for a big pay rise this year. The September hike in minimum wages is likely
to lead to further demand from lower-paid workers, and therefore higher
prices, at a time when monthly inflation was expected to have stabilised at
low single figures.
The rise will also affect Brazil's social security system, which uses the
minimum wage as a benchmark for benefits and pensions.
It is likely to raise the annual cost of total benefits by at least Dollars
500m and take the government's budget into deficit. A balanced budget and
strict money supply rules are the key to underpinning the Real and
preventing yet another inflationary cycle.
Meanwhile, economists said frost in southern Brazil since the weekend would
have a limited effect on domestic food prices.
Brazil has halted all new coffee exports indefinitely and cancelled
contracts agreed upon since the weekend after the worst frost in more than a
decade damaged 15 to 30 per cent of next year's coffee crop.
Although vegetable prices have already started to rise, they are likely to
be balanced by falling meat prices as farmers sell cattle rather than see
their quality decline on frost-affected pasture.
However, due to other price increases in advance of the launch of the Real,
overall inflation is now expected to top 50 per cent for June, technically
taking Brazil into hyper-inflation.
Coffee consolidates gains, Page 34
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BRZ  Brazil, South America.
</CN>
