<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Caracas attacked over drastic powers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera's administration was criticised
yesterday for assuming wide new powers in an attempt to tackle a gathering
financial crisis.
The new measures, not yet fully defined, represent the strongest set of
interventionist policies in Venezuela since the late 1980s, when the
administration of President Carlos Andres Perez launched a series of
market-oriented reforms.
The measures include controls on foreign exchange transactions and on many
prices of basic consumer goods and services, the suspension of certain basic
civil and economic liberties, special 'bonus' payments to workers to help
cover transportation and food costs, and stiffer supervision of financial
institutions.
The government also threatened to take harsh action, including fines and
jail, against businesses found to be hoarding merchandise or violating price
controls.
The Caldera administration has been in a financial crisis since it took
office in February, after the collapse of the second-largest Venezuelan
bank, Banco Latino.
'These measures are the result of not wanting to face reality. They are
focussing on effects instead of causes,' said Mr Jorge Redmond, president of
Conindustria, Venezuela's largest association of private industrial
companies.
In New York, analysts at Bear Stearns argued that the controls were not
welcome but 'may not be wholly negative, provided they are temporary tools'.
They could help to stabilise the Venezuelan bolivar, which has been nearly
halved in value this year and which the analysts described as 'oversold'.
Exchange controls began yesterday with a suspension of foreign exchange
transactions at financial institutions for five working days. The rules
covering exchange controls will be defined in a joint resolution, yet to be
announced, by the finance ministry and the central bank.
The new price controls, to be defined in detail by the industry ministry,
cover scores of products: basic food items such as rice, bread, sugar, eggs;
other items such as soap, medicine, toothpaste, car parts, clothing, shoes;
services such as electric power, gas, water, telephones, medical attention,
funerals and dry cleaning.
The third main element among the new measures was the suspension of some
rights guaranteed by the Venezuelan constitution. These include three civil
rights: free movement in and outside the national territory, the
inviolability of the home and protection against unauthorised arrest and
detention, and economic liberties, which cover the right to engage in any
legal economic activity, the right to own property, and the control of
expropriation by the state.
Suspending these freedoms gives the government powers to deal with social
disturbances and allows it greater freedom to apprehend speculators,
hoarders, rumour-mongers and corrupt individuals whom officials have blamed
for many economic troubles.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>VEZ  Venezuela, South America.
</CN>
