<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Albanian diaspora boosts economy: The desperate boat people
of a few years ago are now the country's saviours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fidel Castro called those who fled his dictatorship 'worms', and was deeply
embarrassed when they returned to Cuba as mariposas - well dressed
capitalist butterflies laden with gifts for their families. A similar
transformation is under way for the desperate boat people who in 1990 and
1991 fled Albania on board ancient ships or across mountain paths after the
collapse of the hated regime established by Enver Hoxha, the communist
dictator.
Many are still living miserably and working illegally at humble jobs in
Greece, Italy and further afield. But remittances sent back home at great
personal sacrifice from the more than 300,000 who fled what was once
Europe's most isolated country have become Albania's largest source of
foreign exchange, underpinning an extraordinary 11 per cent growth in gross
domestic product last year after an officially calculated 35 per cent
accumulated decline since 1989.
Remittances rose from virtually zero in 1991 to Dollars 150m (Pounds 99m) in
1992 and more than doubled to Dollars 335m last year. This was three times
the value of exports, at Dollars 112m, and 10 per cent higher than
short-term foreign aid, which declined to Dollars 303m from its 1992 peak of
Dollars 374m. The experience of earlier south European migrations to the
richer parts of Europe indicates that such flows are likely to diminish as
emigres either settle down in their new homes or return. But in the meantime
the physical exodus of a tenth of the population of 3.2m, and much higher
percentage of the economically active, has played a crucial role both in
reducing unemployment and in kick-starting a vibrant free market of small
traders and pavement cafes and financing the importation of more than 40,000
mainly second-hand cars, vans and trucks over the past two years.
Many of the vehicles are of dubious provenance. And much of the luxury foods
and consumer goods are smuggled by fast boat from Italy or from Greece,
avoiding taxes and stimulating crime and corruption. But for most Albanians
the important thing is that the last two years have brought the first taste
of a banana or decent coffee as well as a cornucopia of other western
consumer goods from TV satellite dishes to Coca-Cola.
The wild west atmosphere is calming down as the government introduces
customs duties and new personal taxes - and recruits a small army of tax
officials and financial police to enforce the will of a Democratic party-led
government elected in March 1992.
President Sali Berisha, a former heart specialist who has become the
increasingly powerful head of state, is regarded by western embassies in
Tirana as a leader capable of persuading Albanians to concentrate on
rebuilding their state and economy rather than dreaming of reunification
with some 3m ethnic Albanians who live in neighbouring former Yugoslav
regions of Montenegro, Kosovo and Macedonia.
With more than Dollars 1.5bn pumped into the country over the last three
years, Albania is by far the biggest recipient of western aid and soft loans
per capita in post-communist Europe. A three-year, Dollars 720m public
investment programme for 1994-96 depends largely on the flow continuing at
the current rate of about Dollars 300m a year over this period.
The aim is to make up for five decades of infrastructural neglect and build
a new economic base after the virtual destruction of the old industrial
economy which was based on obsolete Soviet and Chinese technology.
The start of the investment programme essentially marks the beginning of the
second stage of Albania's economic reconstruction. It builds on the
successful economic stabilisation policies of 1991-93 during which prices
were liberalised, subsidies virtually eliminated and inflation reduced from
more than 230 per cent in January 1993 to an expected 20-22 per cent average
for 1994.
At the same time the collective farms were abolished and land was
redistributed in small 3.5-acre plots to the 65 per cent of the population
who live and work in the rural areas. The combination of closing loss-making
plants, freeing trade and dissolving the collectives ensured that the surge
in incomes from remittances and higher farm output sparked off a big
increase in the domestic food supply as well as an import-led consumer boom.
Independent economists say the main challenge facing the government, and
especially the revamped central bank and Finance Ministry, is to resist the
temptation to tax the emerging private sector too harshly. The alternative,
they say, is to focus on encouraging the fledgling banks to improve their
lending capacity.
This would help the thousands of Albanians who have already made small
fortunes in trade to move into construction, food processing and other
industrial production, or tourism, which many see as one of the keys to
Albania's re-emergence as a balanced industrial, agricultural and
service-based economy.
See Business and the Environment page
