<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Portugal urged to open markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Portugal must introduce competition into sheltered areas of its economy to
ensure inflation moves down towards average European Union levels, the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development said. It urged an
overhaul of the regulatory framework and more vigorous privatisation
initiatives to improve the competitiveness of public electricity, water,
transport and telecommunications as well as housing and insurance. Portugal
would emerge from recession this year with economic growth of 1.2 per cent,
rising to 2.3 per cent next year. Higher exports and consumption supported
by lower interest rates would fuel growth. The OECD report coincided with
the swearing-in of a new governor of the Bank of Portugal, Mr Antoio de
Sousa. Mr Eduardo Catroga, finance minister, said the government and the
central bank were both firmly committed to maintaining exchange-rate
stability.
