<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Macedonia misses aid target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Macedonia failed yesterday to win enough aid to meet its mounting foreign
debts. Although Denmark, the Netherlands, France and Switzerland pledged an
undisclosed sum to help finance imports, Mr Michael Wiehen, a World Bank
director who chaired the first meeting of the newly formed aid-to-Macedonia
consortium, said the donors' overall offer was 'quite inadequate in terms of
what, in cash terms, Macedonia needs to regularise its relations with its
creditors'. Mr Ljube Trpeski, Macedonia's minister for international
financial affairs, said that of his country's total Dollars 1.1bn (Pounds
720m) debt, Dollars 194m was owed to the Paris Club of official creditors
and Dollars 514m to commercial banks. Mr Wiehen said Macedonia would need to
pay Paris Club creditors Dollars 50m and institutions such as the European
Investment Bank Dollars 45m, even to get a rescheduling deal from them.
