FT  29 JUN 94 / SPD backs post-telecom sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The opposition Social Democratic party (SPD) made a last-minute decision to
back the sale of Germany's state-owned postal and telecommunications
service, clearing the way for the country's largest privatisation. The SPD
decision guarantees a two-thirds majority for the government in a vote today
in the Bundestag to change Article 73 of the constitution which says that
postal and telecommunications services are the exclusive responsibility of
the state. Following the vote the present company which employs 670,000
people will be turned into three state-owned joint stock companies on
January 1, 1995: Deutsche Telekom, Postdienst, the postal service, and
Postbank, the banking arm. Telekom has said it wants to float 30 per cent of
its equity on the stock market in 1996 to raise badly needed capital.
