<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Bulgaria begins mass sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By THEODOR TROEV
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SOFIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bulgaria's long-delayed mass privatisation through vouchers came into force
yesterday. The scheme, modelled on the pioneering Czech sell-off, entitles
adult Bulgarians to privatisation vouchers representing assets with a book
value of Lev25,000 (about Pounds 300) on payment of Lev500. The vouchers can
be exchanged for shares in around 500 state-owned enterprises, with assets
totalling Lev110.8bn. Private investment funds will be created to manage and
invest the vouchers on behalf of the public. Officials from the newly
founded Centre for Mass Privatisation are drafting a separate law to govern
investment funds. Meanwhile, Bulgaria is due to sign a debt reduction
agreement with the London Club of commercial bank creditors in Sofia today.
The deal will cut by 47.1 per cent Bulgaria's Dollars 8.16bn debt to more
than 300 commercial creditor banks led by Deutsche Bank.
</TEXT>
