<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Brussels VAT plan to be revealed soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission is to make recommendations by the end of October on
whether value added tax should be levied on goods and services sold in the
EU at the rate prevailing in the country of origin, Ms Christiane Scrivener,
the commissioner for customs and indirect taxation, said yesterday. Ms
Scrivener reaffirmed the Commission's commitment in principle to a shift to
the 'origin system' of levying VAT. Speaking at a conference discussing the
existing transitional VAT arrangements, she said that agreement to the
change - which must be ratified by the council of ministers - would require
that the new system would simplify obligations to business and ensure that
there was no additional risk of fraud. The EU is theoretically committed to
introducing the origin-based system to replace the existing transitional
system of VAT harmonisation across Europe by the start of 1997.
</TEXT>
