<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / Unilever's chief attacks EU policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Business Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Michael Perry, joint chairman of Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch consumer
products group, last night accused European Union leaders of showing
'astonishing lack of focus' in tackling the region's flagging economic
growth and competitiveness.
Many governments were 'hell-bent on creating and preserving rigidities',
instead of helping their economies adapt to the challenge of fast-growing
Asian competition, he said. 'I don't believe governments have begun to
address the issues.'
His criticisms of EU policy failures - in a speech to the Royal Institute of
International Affairs in London and in an interview - are among the toughest
recently by a top European industrialist.
They were part of a generally bleak assessment of Europe's economic
performance, which underlined the threat to its prosperity from Asian
rivals. He dismissed as 'alarmingly irresponsible' suggestions that Europe
could return to full employment this decade.
Sir Michael said governments should 'stop continually shifting burdens on to
employers in order to avoid what should properly be hard political choices
about public spending priorities'.
The EU was imposing too many costly and unnecessary regulations on business
which, he said, were exemplified by its recent Works Council Directive.
'What amazes me is that anyone should think it is going to make the
slightest contribution to solving the central economic question of today -
making Europe more competitive,' he said.
European companies must embrace change by improving innovation and quality,
cutting costs and entering new markets, he said. Their most urgent task was
to persuade employees of the need for more flexible working practices.
The EU needed to stimulate efficiency by implementing the Uruguay Round
trade deal and pressing ahead with its single market.
However, Sir Michael feared growing resistance to industrial restructuring.
'One is concerned that governments are less willing to accept the full
consequences of driving costs out of the economy than when the single market
was set up,' he said.
Governments should seek a partnership with business to improve education,
re-skilling and infrastructure, and not engage in 'pseudo-activity by
attempting to second-guess industrial decisions'.
He said the UK political climate was more positive than in some continental
countries: 'We in Britain reckon our government is listening to business
needs more closely than in other parts of Europe.'
However, Europe's unemployment would probably not fall below 6 per cent for
the rest of the decade, even if annual growth averaged 3.5 per cent. 'That
is why I find the glib talk about 'full employment' . . . in some political
circles alarmingly irresponsible,' Sir Michael said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
