<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Rail strike still on as talks fail to reach deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tomorrow's 24-hour strike by railway signalling staff is still on after
talks at Acas were adjourned early this morning without a settlement.
Railtrack, the rail network operator, and RMT union officials failed to
reach an agreement after 10 1/2 hours of intensive negotiations at the
conciliation service, but they agreed to resume at 10am today.
Mr David Armstrong, Railtrack's industrial relations director, said after
the talks that the union had declined to lift the strike threat for
tomorrow. 'We have not made as much progress as I would have expected. I am
disappointed about that,' he added.
Mr Vernon Hince, RMT's assistant general secretary, said: 'A strike is still
firmly on, but we are still talking. At the present time there is still a
long way to go. It is a very complicated situation.'
Neither side would reveal what they had achieved so far in their marathon
negotiations.
Railtrack still insists it cannot pay increases for past productivity while
the union says there must be an 11 per cent interim pay award for past
performance. Railtrack has already offered 2.5 per cent for all its
employees.
Dobson backs rail union, Page 11
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
