<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Newspapers up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Telegraph rebounded as it fought to minimise the effect of the recent
price cut which last week poured fuel on the smouldering newspaper price
war.
Chairman Mr Conrad Black was reported to be considering taking the newspaper
back into private hands if the shares fell further. More controversially, he
claimed that the drop in profits from the price reduction would be limited
to no more than Pounds 5m to Pounds 10m a year.
Elsewhere, there was widespread relief that middle market newspapers Daily
Mail and Daily Express had resisted the pressure to cut their cover prices
and had taken the less expensive promotional path. Daily Mail Trust 'A'
shares bounced 23 to 893p and Express parent United Newspapers recovered 13
to 498p.
