<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow rebounds as dollar
improves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks surged yesterday afternoon as the dollar firmed without further
intervention by the world's central banks, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 48.56 higher at 3,685.50,
rebounding strongly from a 26-point decline at the opening. The more broadly
based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was up 4.51 at 447.31, even though there was an
even split between New York SE rises and declines. Volume was a moderate
250m shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite lagged behind with a
0.85 decline to 425.45, but the Nasdaq composite enjoyed a handsome gain of
8.89 at 702.68.
From the first hour of trade, investors defied expectations of a powerful
after-shock on the heels of Friday's 62-point Dow sell-off. At first, the
news from the foreign exchange markets was barely supportive, with the US
currency slipping below the Y100 mark in overnight trading and flirting with
that level throughout the morning.
But the relative stability of the dollar, without any further intervention,
seemed to be enough to shore up the bond market. Treasuries started out with
moderate losses, but staged an impressive rally of their own during the
afternoon.
The blue chips fared even better, gaining a foothold on positive ground by
mid-morning and never turning back. Two stocks, Caterpillar and Walt Disney,
led the advance.
Shares in the world's biggest maker of earth-moving equipment improved
Dollars 4 to Dollars 105 1/8 , even though a strike by 14,000 production
workers dragged into its second week. Bargain hunters appeared to be taking
advantage of a stock well off its 52-week high of Dollars 121 3/8 .
Walt Disney, meanwhile, climbed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 43. The company's
new film, The Lion King, became the third biggest Hollywood release of all
time, selling Dollars 41m worth of tickets in its first weekend.
The Big Three US car makers were back in favour, with Ford Motor advancing
Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 59 3/4 , General Motors up Dollars 2 at Dollars 52
3/8 and Chrysler adding Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 47 3/4 .
Banking issues improved, including JP Morgan, Dollars 1 1/2 ahead at Dollars
63 3/8 . Technology stocks were generally higher as well, led by IBM. Big
Blue rose Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 61 5/8 in spite of reports that
production delays were forcing Big Blue to scale back the launch of its
much-vaunted PowerPC line of personal computers.
A rebound by computer-related stocks helped the Nasdaq climb off its weakest
close in a year on Friday. Wellfleet jumped Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 25 1/2
, Microsoft climbed Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 51 7/8 and Oracle added Dollars
1 1/8 at Dollars 37 3/4 .
</TEXT>
<XX>
