FT  28 JUN 94 / International Company News: Court gives BHP time to defend
ADollars 4bn lawsuit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Victoria Supreme Court yesterday set aside an interlocutory judgment for
damages against Broken Hill Proprietary, in respect of the ADollars 4bn
(USDollars 2.9bn) environmental lawsuit brought against the large Australian
resources company by villagers living around the Ok Tedi copper mine in
western Papua New Guinea.
BHP had been found guilty by default earlier this month because it failed to
lodge a defence to the writ within a 30-day period - although lawyers
quibbled over the precise deadline.
The Australian company, which manages the mine, has since submitted its
defence documents and said it will contest the action. The biggest of
Australia's natural resource groups, BHP is due to report its full-year
results on Friday.
