<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / International Company News: Shares in US machine tool maker
tumble 24%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Giddings &amp; Lewis, the US machine tool manufacturer, fell 24 per
cent yesterday when the company announced it expected 1994 earnings per
share to be some 20 per cent below Wall Street forecasts.
It blamed the shortfall in part on competitive industry pricing, which
resulted from Europe's soft machine tools market.
The stock, which is quoted on the Nasdaq market, closed at Dollars 15 3/4 ,
down Dollars 5 on the day.
The company said it expected second-quarter earnings per share to be flat or
slightly above the 20 cents earned in the first quarter, while for the full
year earnings were likely to be 20 per cent below the Dollars 1.35 to
Dollars 1.45 being forecast by analysts.
The company had earnings per share of 34 cents in the second quarter of last
year with Dollars 1.31 in 1993 as a whole.
Mr Joseph Coppola, chairman, said a number of contracts booked in prior
periods had proved more costly than anticipated.
In addition, competitive pressures meant that 1994 gross margins, which the
company had anticipated to be around 24-25 per cent, should instead be in
the 22-23 per cent range - even though the group expected continued growth
in quarterly bookings compared with last year.
The soft market for machine tools in Europe had meant lower bookings for the
company's operations there and also affected worldwide pricing: competitors
suffering sharp order declines overseas were bidding aggressively for
contracts in the US, creating more intense pricing pressure.
Furthermore, the company's automation technology group, which makes highly
engineered machine tools and cellular systems, had suffered weaker than
expected bookings because US purchasers remained cautious about the economy.
On the positive side, its domestic automotive business remained strong.
</TEXT>
