<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / International Company News: Norwegians to buy Bond
Helicopters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Helikopter Service, the Norwegian helicopter group, yesterday announced
plans to acquire Aberdeen-based Bond Helicopters in a cash-plus-shares deal
which values Bond at NKr800m (Dollars 115m).
The deal will create the world's largest helicopter group with a fleet of
169 aircraft and annual turnover of NKr2.5bn. Following four years of
co-operation between the two groups, HS yesterday acquired 49 per cent of
Bond and will take over the remaining 51 per cent during the next three
years.
The owners of Bond will acquire up to 12.2 per cent of the shares of HS
during the amalgamation period, making them the biggest single shareholder;
3i, the UK venture capital company, is disposing of its 30 per cent stake in
Bond.
Mr Christian Brinch, managing director of HS, said the companies would
retain their identities during the next three years and that there would be
no formal changes to management. Mr Brinch will become the managing director
of the new entity.
The merged group with 1,800 employees, 156 helicopters and 13 aircraft will
command 42 per cent of the North Sea market.
</TEXT>
